  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, ultrasound for breast cysts sorts it out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is US. Ultrasound is the best initial investigation to visualize and characterize cystic breast masses due to its ability to differentiate fluid-filled structures from solid lesions in real-time.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUltrasound utilizes high-frequency sound waves to create images of breast tissue. For cystic masses, it typically reveals an anechoic (black, fluid-filled) lesion with smooth, thin walls and characteristic posterior acoustic enhancement, which indicates sound waves passing unimpeded through fluid. This allows for definitive diagnosis of a simple cyst, often avoiding further invasive procedures.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (MRI) (Incorrect): While excellent for soft tissue characterization and cancer staging, MRI is not the first-line or best investigation for initial visualization and differentiation of simple cystic breast masses due to its cost, availability, and potential for over-diagnosis.\nOption B (CT) (Incorrect): CT scans are generally not used for primary breast imaging due to radiation exposure, lower resolution for breast tissue compared to other modalities, and poor differentiation of cystic from solid lesions.\nOption C (Mammogram) (Incorrect): Mammography is primarily used for screening and detecting solid masses, calcifications, and architectural distortion. While a cyst may appear as a circumscribed mass on a mammogram, it cannot definitively distinguish between solid and cystic components, often requiring follow-up with ultrasound.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality   | Primary Use Case                                | Strength for Cysts                                   | Limitation for Cysts                                  |\n|------------|-------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------|\n| US         | Differentiating solid from cystic masses, guided biopsy | Definitive diagnosis of simple cysts (anechoic, enhancement) | Operator-dependent, limited field of view             |\n| Mammogram  | Breast cancer screening, detecting calcifications | Can identify circumscribed masses                    | Cannot definitively distinguish solid from cystic     |\n| MRI        | High-risk screening, cancer staging, implant evaluation | Can characterize complex cysts, extent of disease    | High cost, not first-line for simple cysts, contrast needed |\n| CT         | Staging of advanced cancer, not primary breast imaging | Poor                                                 | High radiation, poor resolution for breast tissue     |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: US is the go-to for 'cystic or solid?' in the breast.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a simple breast cyst appears as a well-circumscribed, anechoic (black) lesion with a thin, imperceptible wall and prominent posterior acoustic enhancement (a bright area behind the cyst).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) Appropriateness Criteria for Breast Imaging (2022) recommends ultrasound as the primary modality for evaluating palpable breast masses in women under 30 and for characterizing masses seen on mammography.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | MRI | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | CT | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Mammogram | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | US | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
