  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lobular: The bilateral breast cancer you can't ignore!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Lobular carcinoma. This type of breast cancer is notoriously multifocal and often bilateral, making it a critical consideration when evaluating a patient with a bilateral breast mass.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInvasive lobular carcinoma (ILC) is characterized by its unique infiltrative growth pattern, often described as 'Indian file' arrangement, due to the loss of E-cadherin expression. This lack of cell-to-cell adhesion allows tumor cells to spread diffusely through the breast tissue, making it difficult to detect on imaging and contributing to its higher rates of multifocality and bilaterality compared to invasive ductal carcinoma. Its diffuse nature also makes it more challenging to palpate as a distinct mass.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Paget disease) (Incorrect): Paget disease of the breast is a rare form of breast cancer involving the skin of the nipple and areola, almost exclusively unilateral.\nOption C (Mucinous carcinoma) (Incorrect): Mucinous carcinoma is a rare, distinct subtype of invasive ductal carcinoma, typically presenting as a well-circumscribed, unilateral mass.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Invasive Lobular Carcinoma (ILC) | Invasive Ductal Carcinoma (IDC) | Paget Disease of the Nipple |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Bilaterality** | Highest incidence (6-28%) | Low (1-2%) | Extremely rare (typically unilateral) |\n| **Histology** | Discohesive cells, 'Indian file' pattern, loss of E-cadherin | Ductal formation, pleomorphic cells | Intraepidermal adenocarcinoma cells |\n| **Palpation** | Often subtle, diffuse thickening | Discrete mass | Nipple/areola eczema-like changes |\n| **Imaging** | Architectural distortion, often subtle, can be missed on mammography | Spiculated mass, microcalcifications | Nipple thickening, erosion, erythema |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think lobular for multifocal or bilateral breast cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammography, lobular carcinoma often presents as architectural distortion or a subtle, ill-defined mass rather than a dense, spiculated lesion, making it challenging to detect. Ultrasound may show a hypoechoic mass with posterior shadowing. MRI is often superior for detecting the extent of disease and bilaterality due to its diffuse growth pattern.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (Version 1.2024) recommend MRI for staging in patients with newly diagnosed lobular carcinoma due to its higher rates of multifocality and bilaterality.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Paget disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lobular carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Mucinous carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
