  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Clear fluid, clear conscience: simple cyst, simple follow-up.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is to reassure the patient and reassess in 4 weeks. This approach is based on the benign nature of a simple breast cyst that completely resolves after aspiration of clear fluid, with a short follow-up to confirm resolution.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA painless breast lump in a 30-year-old female, identified as a simple cyst on ultrasound, and yielding clear fluid upon complete aspiration, is overwhelmingly benign. Aspiration serves both diagnostic and therapeutic purposes. The complete resolution of the mass after aspiration of clear fluid confirms its benign nature. Reassurance is paramount, and a short follow-up ensures no recurrence or residual mass, which would warrant further investigation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"Do nothing and no follow-up\" is too absolute. While the lesion is likely benign, a short follow-up is prudent to ensure complete resolution and patient reassurance.\nOption B (Incorrect): Sending clear cyst fluid for cytology is not recommended due to low diagnostic yield and high false-positive/negative rates. Mastectomy is an extreme and inappropriate intervention for a simple cyst.\nOption D (Incorrect): Simple breast cysts do not \"change to cancer.\" Mastectomy is a radical and completely unwarranted procedure for this presentation.\nOption E (Incorrect): Contraceptive pills have no role in the management or prevention of simple breast cysts.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Simple Cyst | Complicated Cyst | Complex Cyst |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Ultrasound | Anechoic, thin wall, posterior enhancement | Anechoic with internal echoes/debris, no solid component | Thick wall, septations, solid components |\n| Aspiration | Clear fluid, complete resolution | Turbid/bloody fluid, may resolve | Residual mass, often bloody fluid |\n| Management | Reassurance, 4-6 week follow-up | Cytology of fluid, short-term follow-up, consider biopsy if persistent | Biopsy (core or excisional) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Clear fluid from a simple cyst? Reassure and recheck.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a simple breast cyst appears as an anechoic (black) lesion with a thin, imperceptible wall, posterior acoustic enhancement, and no internal echoes or solid components.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) BI-RADS Atlas 5th Edition (2013) recommends that a simple cyst (BI-RADS 2) requires no further action. However, clinical practice often includes a short follow-up after aspiration.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Do nothing and no follow-up. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Send the aspirated content for cytology and if abnormal do mastectomy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Reassure the patient that this lump is a cyst and reassess her in 4 weeks. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Book the patient for mastectomy as this cyst may change to cancer. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Put the patient on contraceptive pills and send her home. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
