  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't be radical, be modern: save the muscle, save the breast!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. Radical mastectomy, as originally described by Halsted, is rarely performed in modern surgical oncology due to its significant morbidity and the availability of less invasive, equally effective alternatives. Therefore, stating it is 'the choice of surgery' is incorrect.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nModern breast cancer surgery prioritizes oncologic efficacy with minimal morbidity. Modified Radical Mastectomy (MRM), which preserves the pectoralis muscles, is the standard mastectomy procedure. Breast-conserving surgery (BCS) followed by radiation therapy is often preferred for early-stage disease, offering comparable survival outcomes to mastectomy while preserving the breast. The choice of surgery is individualized based on tumor characteristics, patient preference, and genetic factors.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): A 2 cm mass (T1) with no axillary lymph node involvement (N0) and no distant metastasis (M0) correctly classifies as Stage I breast cancer according to the AJCC TNM staging system. This statement is true.\nOption B (Incorrect): For pre-menopausal women with positive axillary lymph nodes, systemic chemotherapy is a critical component of adjuvant therapy to reduce the risk of recurrence and improve survival outcomes. This statement is true.\nOption D (Incorrect): Annual mammography of the contralateral breast is a standard component of surveillance for patients with a history of breast cancer, aimed at detecting new primary cancers or recurrence. This statement is true.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Surgical Procedure | Description | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|\n| Radical Mastectomy (Halsted) | Removal of breast, pectoralis major/minor muscles, axillary lymph nodes | Rarely performed; high morbidity |\n| Modified Radical Mastectomy (MRM) | Removal of breast, axillary lymph nodes, preservation of pectoralis muscles | Standard mastectomy; preserves chest wall muscles |\n| Breast-Conserving Surgery (BCS) | Lumpectomy + sentinel lymph node biopsy/axillary dissection + radiation therapy | Preserves breast; requires radiation |\n| Simple Mastectomy | Removal of breast tissue only | No axillary dissection; often for DCIS or prophylaxis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Radical mastectomy is a historical procedure, not the modern choice.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammography, a breast mass would appear as a density, potentially with spiculations or architectural distortion. Intraoperatively, a radical mastectomy would involve extensive dissection of the chest wall, including removal of both pectoralis muscles, which is distinct from a modified radical mastectomy where these muscles are preserved.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Clinical Practice Guidelines in Oncology – Breast Cancer (latest version). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for breast cancer staging, treatment, and surveillance, including surgical options and adjuvant therapies.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 2 cm mass with free axilla is stage I | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Chemotherapy is must for pre-menopausal with +ve axilla | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Radical mastectomy is the choice of surgery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Yearly mammogram for contra-lateral breast | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
