  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Adolescent breast lumps: Think 'fibro-friendly'!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. This question correctly identifies fibroadenoma as the most probable diagnosis in a 13-year-old female presenting with a soft, tender, non-cyclical breast mass. The patient's age and the lack of cyclical symptoms are key discriminators in this clinical scenario.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFibroadenomas are benign biphasic tumors composed of both epithelial and stromal elements, making them the most common breast mass in adolescent and young women. They typically present as solitary, mobile, firm, rubbery, and non-tender masses, though tenderness can occasionally be present. Their growth is often hormone-dependent but usually not overtly cyclical like fibrocystic changes, aligning with the patient's denial of aggravation or relief by special conditions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Fibrocystic disease) (Incorrect): Fibrocystic changes are rare in a 13-year-old and typically present with cyclical pain and tenderness, often with multiple masses, which contradicts the patient's age and symptom description. This condition is more common in women aged 20-50.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Fibroadenoma | Fibrocystic Changes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Typical Age | Adolescents, young women (15-35 years) | Women 20-50 years |\n| Presentation | Solitary, mobile, firm/rubbery, non-tender | Often multiple, tender, cyclical pain/size changes |\n| Cyclical Symptoms | Rare/absent | Common, related to menstrual cycle |\n| Malignant Potential | Very low, no increased risk | No increased risk (unless atypical hyperplasia) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Adolescent breast mass = fibroadenoma until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a fibroadenoma typically appears as a well-circumscribed, oval, hypoechoic mass with a smooth contour and often posterior acoustic enhancement. It may show some internal vascularity on Doppler.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) guidelines for benign breast disease recommend ultrasound as the initial imaging modality for palpable breast masses in young women.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Fibroadenoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Fibrocystic disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
