  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When a rash won't quit, think cancer, not just cream.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe clinical scenario describes a persistent, steroid-refractory rash on the breast areola without nipple discharge. This presentation is highly suspicious for Paget's disease of the breast, a rare form of breast cancer involving the nipple and areola.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMammography is the appropriate initial diagnostic step to evaluate for underlying breast malignancy when Paget's disease is suspected. Paget's disease is often associated with an underlying ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) or invasive breast cancer, which mammography can help identify. It provides crucial information about the extent of disease and guides further management, including biopsy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Antibiotic): Incorrect. A rash that has not improved with corticosteroids is unlikely to be a simple bacterial infection, and empirical antibiotics would delay the diagnosis of a potentially serious condition like Paget's disease.\nOption B (Surgery): Incorrect. While a biopsy (a surgical procedure) is ultimately required for definitive diagnosis of Paget's disease, it is typically performed after initial imaging (like mammography) to assess for underlying breast lesions and guide the biopsy site. 'Surgery' as a general option is too broad and premature as the initial step.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Paget's Disease of the Breast | Eczema/Dermatitis | Inflammatory Breast Cancer |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Appearance** | Unilateral, persistent, scaly, erythematous rash on nipple/areola; may ulcerate | Bilateral, itchy, dry, scaly rash; often responds to steroids | Diffuse erythema, edema, peau d'orange; rapid onset; no distinct mass |\n| **Symptoms** | Itching, burning, tingling; may have nipple discharge (less common) | Intense itching, dryness | Warmth, tenderness, breast enlargement; no distinct mass |\n| **Response to Steroids** | No improvement | Improves | No improvement |\n| **Underlying Pathology** | Intraepidermal adenocarcinoma cells (Paget cells); often associated with underlying DCIS/invasive cancer | Inflammatory skin condition | Dermal lymphatic invasion by carcinoma cells |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Persistent, steroid-refractory nipple/areola rash = rule out Paget's disease with imaging and biopsy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammography, Paget's disease may show skin thickening, nipple retraction, or an underlying mass/calcifications indicative of associated ductal carcinoma. Ultrasound may reveal a hypoechoic mass or ductal ectasia. Biopsy of the nipple/areola lesion is diagnostic.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Breast Cancer Screening and Diagnosis (2023). These guidelines recommend mammography and clinical evaluation for suspicious breast symptoms, including persistent skin changes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Antibiotic | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Surgery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Mammography | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
