  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let mastitis milk your time, treat it right!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Cephalexin or dicloxacillin. Lactation mastitis is most commonly caused by Staphylococcus aureus, and these antibiotics provide excellent first-line oral coverage against this pathogen.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCephalexin (a first-generation cephalosporin) and dicloxacillin (a penicillinase-resistant penicillin) are both beta-lactam antibiotics that inhibit bacterial cell wall synthesis. They are highly effective against methicillin-sensitive Staphylococcus aureus (MSSA) and Streptococcus species, which are the predominant organisms in community-acquired mastitis. Their established safety profile for breastfeeding mothers makes them the preferred initial treatment choice.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Doxycycline): Incorrect. While it has some staphylococcal coverage, it is not considered first-line for mastitis and has theoretical concerns regarding use in breastfeeding infants, though often deemed low risk for short courses.\nOption B (Ciprofloxacin): Incorrect. A fluoroquinolone, it is generally not first-line for mastitis due to increasing resistance, potential for adverse effects, and concerns about cartilage damage in breastfeeding infants.\nOption C (Ceftriaxone): Incorrect. A third-generation cephalosporin, ceftriaxone is a parenteral antibiotic with a broader spectrum, typically reserved for more severe infections, hospitalized patients, or specific resistant organisms, not routine oral outpatient mastitis.\nOption D (Gentamicin): Incorrect. An aminoglycoside, gentamicin is a parenteral antibiotic with significant toxicity (nephrotoxicity, ototoxicity) and is not used for outpatient oral treatment of mastitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Antibiotic | Class | Common Use in Mastitis | Key Consideration |\n| :--------- | :---- | :--------------------- | :----------------- |\n| Cephalexin | 1st Gen Cephalosporin | First-line oral for MSSA | Well-tolerated, safe in breastfeeding |\n| Dicloxacillin | Penicillinase-resistant Penicillin | First-line oral for MSSA | Similar to cephalexin, safe in breastfeeding |\n| Clindamycin | Lincosamide | Alternative for penicillin allergy or MRSA suspicion | Good for anaerobic coverage, C. diff risk |\n| Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole (TMP-SMX) | Sulfonamide | Alternative for MRSA suspicion | Avoid in late pregnancy/neonates due to kernicterus risk |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cephalexin or dicloxacillin are first-line for lactation mastitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound is the imaging modality of choice to evaluate for abscess formation in mastitis, which would necessitate drainage. No image was provided in the question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 197 (2018) recommends oral antibiotics like dicloxacillin or cephalexin for 10-14 days for mastitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Doxycycline | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Ciprofloxacin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Ceftriaxone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Gentamicin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Cephalexin or dicloxacillin | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
