  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Clear fluid, resolved lump: you're good to go!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks which finding allows for discharge without further immediate follow-up. A simple breast cyst with serous fluid that completely resolves after aspiration is a benign finding that typically does not require further appointments.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBreast cysts are common benign lesions. Aspiration of a simple cyst yielding clear, serous fluid, followed by complete resolution of the mass, is a reassuring sign. This procedure is both diagnostic and therapeutic. The absence of refilling indicates that the cyst wall is not actively secreting fluid or that the underlying cause has resolved, further supporting a benign etiology and negating the need for immediate re-evaluation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Blood on aspiration is a red flag. Bloody aspirate from a breast cyst warrants further investigation, including cytology and potentially imaging or biopsy, due to an increased risk of malignancy.\nOption C (Incorrect): A solid breast mass, regardless of clinical impression, always requires triple assessment (clinical exam, imaging, and tissue sampling/biopsy) to rule out malignancy. It cannot be dismissed without further investigation.\nOption D (Incorrect): Fibrocystic change on histological examination is a benign diagnosis, but it implies a biopsy has already been performed. The question asks what makes you \"leave her without appointment\" at an earlier stage. While fibrocystic changes are benign, the presence of a new lump often warrants initial investigation, and a histological diagnosis means an appointment and procedure have already occurred. Furthermore, some fibrocystic changes (e.g., atypical hyperplasia) do require follow-up.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Finding | Management | Urgency |\n|---|---|---|\n| Simple cyst, serous fluid, resolves | Observe, no immediate follow-up | Low |\n| Cyst, bloody fluid | Cytology, imaging, possible biopsy | High |\n| Solid mass | Triple assessment (imaging, biopsy) | High |\n| Fibrocystic change (histology) | Benign, but follow-up based on specific type and clinical context | Variable |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Clear cyst aspirate that resolves means no immediate follow-up.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a simple cyst appears as an anechoic, well-circumscribed lesion with posterior acoustic enhancement. Aspiration confirms its cystic nature.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) BI-RADS Atlas (2013/2024): A simple cyst is classified as BI-RADS 2 (Benign), requiring no further action.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cystic lesion with serous fluid that not refill again | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Blood on aspiration | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Solid | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Fibrocystic change on histological examination | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
