  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Aspirate, resolve, relax: simple cysts are benign.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT, as a breast mass that is cystic and does not refill after aspiration is characteristic of a simple cyst, which is a definitively benign finding. This clinical scenario often allows for reassurance and avoids further invasive procedures.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSimple breast cysts are fluid-filled sacs that arise from the terminal ductal lobular unit. Aspiration of the fluid confirms its cystic nature. If the mass completely resolves upon aspiration and does not recur, it indicates a simple cyst, which carries no malignant potential. This procedure is both diagnostic and therapeutic, providing immediate relief and confirming benignity without the need for biopsy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): While cytology showing fibrocystic disease confirms a benign process, \"fibrocystic disease\" is a broad term for benign changes, not always presenting as a distinct \"mass\" that is aspirated in the same way a simple cyst is. Furthermore, the question asks what a benign breast mass *is*, and a simple cyst that resolves with aspiration is a very specific and common presentation of a benign mass.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Benign Breast Lesion | Key Characteristics | Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| Simple Cyst | Fluid-filled, smooth walls on imaging, resolves with aspiration, non-refilling | Aspiration (diagnostic & therapeutic), observation |\n| Fibroadenoma | Solid, mobile, rubbery mass; well-circumscribed on imaging | Observation, excision if growing or symptomatic, core biopsy for diagnosis |\n| Fibrocystic Changes | Lumpy, tender breasts, often bilateral; diffuse or localized thickening | Symptomatic relief, observation, reassurance |\n| Intraductal Papilloma | Small, benign tumor in a milk duct, often causes nipple discharge | Excision due to potential for atypical hyperplasia or malignancy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: A simple cyst that aspirates clear fluid and resolves is benign.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a simple cyst appears as an anechoic (black) lesion with a thin, smooth wall, posterior acoustic enhancement, and no internal vascularity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) BI-RADS Atlas (2013/2024) recommends a BI-RADS 2 (benign) classification for simple cysts, requiring no further follow-up.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | that is cystic and dose not refill after aspiration | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | cytology shows fibrocystic disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
