  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For appendicitis, CT sees all; don't guess, just scan.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is CT scan. It is widely recognized as the most accurate non-invasive imaging modality for diagnosing acute appendicitis in adults due to its high sensitivity and specificity, allowing for clear visualization of the appendix and surrounding structures.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCT scan offers superior spatial resolution compared to ultrasound, enabling precise identification of an inflamed appendix, periappendiceal fat stranding, and fluid collections. Its ability to visualize the entire abdomen also helps rule out other pathologies mimicking appendicitis, thereby reducing negative appendectomy rates and improving diagnostic certainty. This comprehensive view is crucial for surgical planning.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (US) (Incorrect): While useful, especially in children and pregnant women to avoid radiation, ultrasound is operator-dependent and generally has lower sensitivity and specificity than CT in adult patients, particularly those with obesity or retrocecal appendix.\nOption B (Diagnostic laparoscopy) (Incorrect): Although highly accurate and potentially therapeutic, diagnostic laparoscopy is an invasive surgical procedure requiring general anesthesia. It is typically reserved for cases with equivocal imaging findings or when there is a high clinical suspicion for appendicitis and surgical intervention is already being considered, rather than being the primary diagnostic tool.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Diagnostic Tool | Accuracy (Adults) | Invasiveness | Radiation Exposure | Best Use Case |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| CT Scan | High (Sensitivity 90-98%, Specificity 90-97%) | Non-invasive | Yes | Most adults, equivocal cases |\n| Ultrasound (US) | Moderate (Sensitivity 75-90%, Specificity 85-95%) | Non-invasive | No | Children, pregnant women, initial screening |\n| Diagnostic Laparoscopy | Very High (Near 100%) | Invasive | No | Equivocal cases after imaging, high clinical suspicion, therapeutic intent |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: When in doubt for adult appendicitis, CT is the gold standard.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, an inflamed appendix appears as a dilated, non-compressible, fluid-filled tubular structure (>6mm diameter) with wall thickening, periappendiceal fat stranding, and sometimes an appendicolith.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Appendicitis (2020) recommend CT scan as the preferred imaging modality for suspected acute appendicitis in adults.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | US | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Diagnostic laparoscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | CT scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
