  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the RUQ aches and labs show bile's plight, think cholecystitis, day and night!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Acute Cholecystitis. The patient's presentation with right hypochondrial pain, nausea, vomiting, leukocytosis, and elevated alkaline phosphatase and bilirubin levels is classic for acute inflammation and obstruction of the gallbladder.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute cholecystitis typically results from obstruction of the cystic duct by a gallstone, leading to bile stasis, inflammation, and often secondary bacterial infection. This obstruction causes the characteristic right upper quadrant pain, often radiating to the back or shoulder, and elicits a positive Murphy's sign on examination. The elevated WBC count reflects the inflammatory response, while the elevated alkaline phosphatase and bilirubin suggest some degree of biliary obstruction, which can occur with severe inflammation or associated choledocholithiasis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Acute appendicitis) (Incorrect): Appendicitis typically presents with periumbilical pain migrating to the right lower quadrant, and would not cause elevated alkaline phosphatase or bilirubin.\nOption C (Perforated peptic ulcer) (Incorrect): A perforated ulcer causes sudden, severe, generalized abdominal pain with signs of peritonitis (e.g., board-like rigidity) and free air on imaging, not typically localized RUQ pain with cholestatic labs.\nOption D (Acute pancreatitis) (Incorrect): While gallstones can cause pancreatitis, the primary pain location is typically epigastric radiating to the back, and the hallmark lab findings are elevated amylase and lipase, not primarily elevated alkaline phosphatase and bilirubin.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Cholecystitis | Acute Appendicitis | Acute Pancreatitis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Pain Location** | Right Hypochondrium (RUQ) | Periumbilical to RLQ | Epigastric, often radiating to back |\n| **Key Symptoms** | Nausea, vomiting, fever, Murphy's sign | Nausea, vomiting, anorexia, rebound tenderness | Nausea, vomiting, severe pain, tenderness |\n| **Distinguishing Labs** | High WBC, high ALP, high Bilirubin | High WBC | High Amylase/Lipase |\n| **Primary Cause** | Gallstone obstructing cystic duct | Obstruction of appendiceal lumen | Gallstones or alcohol abuse |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: RUQ pain + fever + cholestatic labs = Acute Cholecystitis until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound is the initial imaging modality of choice, revealing gallstones, gallbladder wall thickening (>3mm), pericholecystic fluid, and a sonographic Murphy's sign.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 for the management of acute cholecystitis recommend diagnosis based on local signs of inflammation, systemic signs of inflammation, and imaging findings.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Acute cholecystitis | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Acute appendicitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Perforated peptic ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Acute pancreatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
