  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Catch it early, live long and prosper!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, \"More than 90%,\" because Stage I colon cancer is characterized by tumor invasion limited to the submucosa or muscularis propria without lymph node involvement or distant metastasis, making it highly curable with surgical resection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nStage I colon cancer (T1 or T2, N0, M0) represents early-stage disease where the tumor has not penetrated through the muscularis propria into the serosa or involved regional lymph nodes. This localized nature allows for complete surgical excision, which is the cornerstone of treatment. The absence of lymphatic or vascular invasion significantly reduces the risk of micrometastasis, contributing to the excellent long-term survival rates observed after curative resection. The prognosis is directly tied to the depth of invasion and lack of nodal or distant spread.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): 70% is too low for Stage I colon cancer, which has a much better prognosis. This survival rate is more typical of later stages, such as Stage III.\nOption C (Incorrect): 40% is significantly too low for Stage I colon cancer. This survival rate is more indicative of advanced, metastatic disease (Stage IV).\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Colon Cancer Stage | TNM Classification | 5-Year Survival Rate |\n| :----------------- | :----------------- | :------------------- |\n| Stage I            | T1-2 N0 M0         | >90%                 |\n| Stage II           | T3-4 N0 M0         | 70-85%               |\n| Stage III          | Any T N1-2 M0      | 50-70%               |\n| Stage IV           | Any T Any N M1     | <20%                 |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Early colon cancer, early cure.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn colonoscopy, a Stage I lesion might appear as a polypoid or sessile mass, potentially with ulceration, but without obvious signs of deep invasion or circumferential involvement. Intraoperatively, the tumor would be confined to the bowel wall, without palpable lymphadenopathy or peritoneal implants.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Colon Cancer (2023). Recommends surgical resection as the primary treatment for Stage I colon cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | More than 90% | ✅ Correct |\n| B | 70% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 40% | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
