  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Annual check-ups keep colon cancer recurrence in check.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 1 year. Routine follow-up after colectomy for colon cancer typically involves annual visits after an initial more intensive period, balancing surveillance efficacy with patient burden and resource utilization.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPost-colectomy surveillance aims to detect local or distant recurrence and metachronous colorectal neoplasms. While the first 2-3 years often involve more frequent visits (e.g., every 3-6 months) for CEA and clinical exams, the standard for routine, long-term follow-up, especially regarding imaging, transitions to an annual schedule for up to 5 years. This annual interval is supported by evidence showing it effectively identifies recurrences while minimizing unnecessary patient anxiety and healthcare costs.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (6 months) (Incorrect): While some components like CEA or clinical exams might be every 6 months in the initial 2-3 years, routine overall follow-up, especially for imaging, is not typically every 6 months for the entire surveillance period.\nOption B (3 months) (Incorrect): This frequency is too aggressive for routine follow-up after the initial post-operative recovery phase and is not supported by standard guidelines for long-term surveillance.\nOption C (9 months) (Incorrect): This is not a standard interval for colon cancer surveillance follow-up and does not align with established guidelines.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Surveillance Component | Frequency (Post-op) | Duration |\n|---|---|---|\n| Clinical Exam & CEA | Every 3-6 months for 2-3 years, then annually | Up to 5 years |\n| CT Chest/Abdomen/Pelvis | Annually | Up to 5 years |\n| Colonoscopy | 1 year post-op, then every 3-5 years if normal | Lifelong |\n| PET Scan | Not routinely recommended | N/A |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Annual follow-up is the standard for routine colon cancer surveillance after initial intensive phase.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn surveillance CT imaging, one would look for liver metastases, lung metastases, or local recurrence at the surgical site. Endoscopy would focus on anastomotic integrity, recurrence at the anastomosis, or new metachronous polyps/cancers in the remaining colon.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Colon Cancer (e.g., 2023). These guidelines recommend annual CT imaging of the chest/abdomen/pelvis for 5 years and annual clinical visits with CEA for 5 years after curative resection.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 6 months | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 3 months | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 9 months | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 1 years | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
