  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Right colon bleeds and grows, left colon obstructs and strains.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, as dyspeptic symptoms are not typically associated with right colon cancer. Right-sided colon cancers usually present with symptoms related to chronic blood loss, anemia, or a palpable mass, rather than upper gastrointestinal complaints.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRight colon cancers often grow quite large before detection because the right colon has a wider lumen and the stool is liquid, making obstruction rare. Their primary presentation is often insidious, characterized by chronic, low-grade blood loss leading to iron deficiency anemia, fatigue, and weakness. A palpable right lower quadrant mass can also be a presenting sign. Melena can occur if there is significant bleeding and sufficient transit time for hemoglobin degradation, while occult blood is almost universally present.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Profound anemia) (Incorrect): Profound anemia, specifically iron deficiency anemia, is a classic presentation of right colon cancer due to chronic, often occult, blood loss.\nOption B (Occult blood) (Incorrect): Occult blood in the stool is a very common finding in right colon cancer, reflecting the chronic bleeding from the tumor.\nOption D (Melena) (Incorrect): While hematochezia is more common with left-sided lesions, significant bleeding from a right-sided colon cancer can manifest as melena if the blood has enough time to be digested during transit.\nOption E (Right lower quadrant mass) (Incorrect): Due to the larger lumen and liquid stool in the right colon, tumors can grow to a considerable size before causing symptoms, often presenting as a palpable mass in the right lower quadrant.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Symptom             | Right Colon Cancer                               | Left Colon Cancer                                  |\n|---------------------|--------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------|\n| Anemia              | Common (iron deficiency from chronic blood loss) | Less common                                        |\n| Bleeding            | Occult blood, melena                             | Hematochezia, bright red blood per rectum          |\n| Obstruction         | Rare (wide lumen, liquid stool)                  | Common (narrow lumen, solid stool)                 |\n| Mass                | Palpable abdominal mass                          | Less common, often detected late                   |\n| Stool changes       | Seldom                                           | Change in bowel habits, tenesmus, pencil stools    |\n| Dyspeptic symptoms  | Not typical                                      | Not typical                                        |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Right-sided colon cancer: Anemia, Mass, Melena. Not dyspepsia.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn colonoscopy, a right-sided colon cancer typically appears as a fungating, ulcerated, or polypoid mass. CT imaging may reveal a focal area of colonic wall thickening, an intraluminal mass, regional lymphadenopathy, or distant metastatic disease, particularly to the liver.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Colon Cancer (Version 2.2024) recommend screening for colorectal cancer and outline diagnostic workup and treatment strategies based on tumor location and stage.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Profound anemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Occult blood | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Dyspeptic symptoms | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Melena | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Right lower quadrant mass | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
