  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Elderly + weight loss + UQ pain = Think pancreatic cancer until proven otherwise.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is Pancreatic Carcinoma. This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the patient's age (70 years), significant weight loss, fatigue, and anemia, which are classic insidious signs of pancreatic malignancy. Upper quadrant pain further localizes the pathology to the pancreas.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPancreatic carcinoma often presents late due to its retroperitoneal location and non-specific early symptoms. The tumor's metabolic demands contribute to cachexia and weight loss, while chronic inflammation or occult bleeding can lead to anemia. The pain typically arises from tumor invasion of surrounding structures or obstruction of the pancreatic duct, often radiating to the back due to retroperitoneal nerve involvement.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Acute pancreatitis typically presents with sudden, severe epigastric pain, nausea, and vomiting, not primarily with chronic weight loss and anemia. While severe acute pancreatitis can cause systemic symptoms, the chronicity implied by weight loss and anemia makes it less likely.\nOption B (Incorrect): Chronic pancreatitis can cause weight loss, fatigue, and pain due to malabsorption and inflammation. However, in a 70-year-old with significant weight loss and anemia, pancreatic carcinoma must be ruled out, as it is a more aggressive and life-threatening condition, and chronic pancreatitis itself is a risk factor for cancer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Pancreatitis | Chronic Pancreatitis | Pancreatic Carcinoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Onset | Sudden, severe | Recurrent/persistent | Insidious, progressive |\n| Pain | Epigastric, radiating to back, severe | Epigastric, variable, often chronic | Epigastric/UQ, radiating to back, dull/gnawing |\n| Weight Loss | Uncommon (unless severe/prolonged) | Common (malabsorption) | Very common, significant |\n| Anemia | Uncommon | Possible (malabsorption/chronic disease) | Common (chronic disease, occult bleed) |\n| Age | Any age | Any age, often middle-aged | Older age (typically >60) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unexplained weight loss, fatigue, and anemia in an elderly patient with upper quadrant pain screams pancreatic cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, pancreatic carcinoma often appears as a hypodense mass with irregular borders, sometimes causing pancreatic duct dilation (double duct sign if common bile duct is also dilated) or vascular encasement. Intraoperatively, a hard, irregular mass may be palpable in the pancreas.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Pancreatic Adenocarcinoma (2023). These guidelines recommend imaging (CT/MRI) and endoscopic ultrasound with biopsy for diagnosis and staging of suspected pancreatic cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Acute pancreatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Chronic pancreatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pancreatic carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
