  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Smoking + fat malabsorption = pancreas in distress.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that chronic pancreatitis is the most fitting diagnosis. The combination of chronic symptoms, a significant risk factor like smoking, and crucially, positive fecal fat indicating exocrine insufficiency, strongly points to this condition.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic pancreatitis is characterized by irreversible morphological changes, typically leading to permanent impairment of exocrine and/or endocrine function. Long-term smoking is a major risk factor, contributing to inflammation and fibrosis. The presence of steatorrhea (positive fecal fat) is a direct consequence of exocrine pancreatic insufficiency, where lipase production is insufficient to digest dietary fats, leading to their excretion in stool. This symptom is a hallmark of advanced chronic pancreatitis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (acute pancreatitis) (Incorrect): While acute pancreatitis presents with similar pain, nausea, and vomiting, it is typically an acute inflammatory process. Fecal fat is not a characteristic finding of acute pancreatitis, as exocrine function is usually preserved or only transiently impaired.\nOption C (pancreatic CA) (Incorrect): Pancreatic cancer can cause abdominal pain, back pain, and weight loss, and in advanced stages, it can lead to exocrine insufficiency and steatorrhea. However, the question describes a constellation of symptoms more typical of a chronic inflammatory process leading to insufficiency, rather than primarily a mass effect or rapid progression often seen with cancer. While smoking is a risk factor for pancreatic cancer, the positive fecal fat points more directly to chronic pancreatic destruction.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Pancreatitis | Chronic Pancreatitis | Pancreatic Cancer |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Onset | Sudden, severe | Gradual, recurrent | Insidious, progressive |\n| Pain | Epigastric, radiating to back | Epigastric, chronic/recurrent, back pain | Epigastric, back pain, often unrelenting |\n| Nausea/Vomiting | Common | Common, especially during flares | Common |\n| Fecal Fat (Steatorrhea) | Rare/Transient | Common, late stage | Possible, if duct obstructed or extensive disease |\n| Risk Factors | Gallstones, alcohol, hypertriglyceridemia | Alcohol, smoking, genetic | Smoking, obesity, chronic pancreatitis |\n| Pancreatic Function | Usually preserved | Exocrine/endocrine insufficiency | Exocrine/endocrine insufficiency (late) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Chronic abdominal pain + smoking + steatorrhea = chronic pancreatitis until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, chronic pancreatitis may show pancreatic atrophy, calcifications, ductal dilation, and pseudocysts. Endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) is highly sensitive for early changes.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline: Management of Chronic Pancreatitis (2020). The 2020 ACG guideline on chronic pancreatitis emphasizes the role of smoking cessation and enzyme replacement therapy for steatorrhea.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | acute pancreatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Chronic pancreatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | pancreatic CA | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
