  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pseudocyst: A common fluid foe, don't let it grow!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nPseudocyst is the most common serious local complication of acute pancreatitis, forming from peripancreatic fluid collections. While many resolve spontaneously, they can become serious if they grow large, rupture, become infected, or cause obstruction of adjacent organs.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPancreatic pseudocysts are encapsulated collections of pancreatic fluid, enzymes, blood, and necrotic debris, typically lacking an epithelial lining. They usually form approximately 4 weeks after an acute attack and are a direct consequence of pancreatic duct disruption or inflammation. Their relatively high prevalence and potential for significant morbidity (e.g., infection, hemorrhage, rupture, obstruction) make them a frequently encountered serious sequela.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Pancreatic abscess is a serious complication, but it is less common than pseudocyst and typically represents an infected necrotic collection rather than a primary fluid collection.\nOption C (Incorrect): Bowel obstruction can occur in severe pancreatitis, often due to inflammation or compression by a large pseudocyst, but it is not the most common serious complication itself.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Description | Seriousness | Incidence |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Acute Fluid Collection | Peripancreatic fluid without a wall, early | Variable, often resolves | Very common (30-50%) |\n| Pseudocyst | Encapsulated fluid collection, >4 weeks | Moderate to High (rupture, infection, obstruction) | Common (5-16%) |\n| Pancreatic Necrosis | Non-viable pancreatic parenchyma | High (especially if infected) | Common (15-20%) |\n| Pancreatic Abscess | Walled-off collection of pus, late | High | Less common (<5%) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pseudocysts are common, but watch for infection or rupture.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a pseudocyst appears as a well-defined, usually round or oval, fluid-density collection adjacent to the pancreas, often with a discernible wall, distinct from acute fluid collections which lack a wall.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInternational Association of Pancreatology/American Pancreatic Association (IAP/APA) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013). Recommends imaging for persistent symptoms or suspicion of complications like pseudocyst.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Abscess | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pseudocyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Bowel obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
