  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Feed the gut early, bypass the pancreas if severe.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nEarly enteral nutrition is the cornerstone of nutritional support in acute pancreatitis, especially in moderate to severe cases. A naso-jejunal tube facilitates this by delivering nutrients distal to the duodenum, minimizing pancreatic stimulation and promoting gut health.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIn acute pancreatitis, the primary goal of nutritional support is to provide adequate calories and protein while minimizing pancreatic stimulation. Enteral nutrition, particularly via a naso-jejunal tube, achieves this by bypassing the stomach and duodenum, thereby reducing the release of cholecystokinin and secretin. This approach helps maintain gut barrier function, reduces bacterial translocation, and is associated with fewer complications compared to total parenteral nutrition.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): TPN (Total Parenteral Nutrition) is generally discouraged as a first-line nutritional support in acute pancreatitis due to higher risks of infection, gut atrophy, and other complications compared to enteral nutrition. It should only be used if enteral feeding is not feasible or tolerated for an extended period.\nOption B (Incorrect): A \"regular diet\" is typically not appropriate in the initial stages of acute pancreatitis, especially if severe, as it can stimulate the pancreas. Dietary modifications are usually introduced gradually as symptoms improve.\nOption C (Incorrect): While high protein is beneficial, \"high Ca\" (calcium) is not a primary dietary focus, and \"low sugar\" is not the most critical initial modification. This option describes a specific diet composition rather than the overall strategy or delivery method for initial nutrition.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nutritional Support Type | Indication in Acute Pancreatitis | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Oral Diet | Mild pancreatitis, resolving symptoms | Physiologic, cost-effective | Not possible if severe or intolerant |\n| Naso-jejunal Tube (Enteral) | Moderate-severe pancreatitis, intolerance to oral | Maintains gut integrity, lower infection risk | Tube placement, potential for intolerance |\n| Naso-gastric Tube (Enteral) | Mild-moderate pancreatitis, if tolerated | Easier placement than NJ, maintains gastric function | May stimulate pancreas more than NJ |\n| TPN (Parenteral) | Enteral feeding not feasible/tolerated >5-7 days | Provides full nutritional support | High infection risk, gut atrophy, cost |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Early enteral nutrition via NJ tube is preferred over TPN in acute pancreatitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nCT imaging of the abdomen is crucial for diagnosing acute pancreatitis, assessing severity (e.g., necrosis, fluid collections), and can guide tube placement if percutaneous access is needed for feeding or drainage.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline for the Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013/2018 update): Recommends early enteral nutrition over parenteral nutrition in patients with acute pancreatitis who cannot tolerate oral feeding.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | TPN | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Regular diet with low sugar | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | High protein ,high ca , low sugar | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Naso-jujenal tube | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
