  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Ecchymosis in flank or belly? Pancreatitis is getting messy!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe diagnosis is acute pancreatitis. The presence of Grey-Turner's sign (flank ecchymosis) and Cullen's sign (periumbilical ecchymosis) are classic indicators of severe acute pancreatitis with retroperitoneal hemorrhage, making this the definitive diagnosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute pancreatitis involves inflammation of the pancreas, often leading to autodigestion by pancreatic enzymes. In severe cases, this can result in necrosis and hemorrhage. Retroperitoneal bleeding can track along fascial planes, manifesting as Cullen's sign (periumbilical ecchymosis due to tracking along the falciform ligament to the subcutaneous tissue around the umbilicus) and Grey-Turner's sign (flank ecchymosis due to tracking along the retroperitoneal space to the flank). These signs, though rare, are highly specific for severe hemorrhagic pancreatitis and indicate a poor prognosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Acute cholecystitis) (Incorrect): While acute cholecystitis can present with RUQ pain, nausea, and vomiting, it does not typically cause Grey-Turner's or Cullen's signs, which are indicative of retroperitoneal hemorrhage. Cholecystitis is inflammation of the gallbladder, not the pancreas, and its complications do not involve widespread retroperitoneal bleeding.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Pancreatitis (Severe) | Acute Cholecystitis |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pain Location | Epigastric, radiating to back | RUQ, radiating to right shoulder/scapula |\n| Classic Signs | Cullen's, Grey-Turner's | Murphy's sign |\n| Etiology | Gallstones, alcohol, hypertriglyceridemia | Gallstones obstructing cystic duct |\n| Complications | Necrosis, pseudocyst, hemorrhage, ARDS | Gallbladder perforation, empyema, gangrene |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cullen's and Grey-Turner's signs scream severe hemorrhagic pancreatitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, severe acute pancreatitis would show pancreatic edema, necrosis, peripancreatic fluid collections, and potentially retroperitoneal hemorrhage. Cullen's and Grey-Turner's signs are clinical findings, but the underlying hemorrhage would be visible on imaging.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline: Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013). Recommends early aggressive intravenous hydration and identifies prognostic factors for severe disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Acute pancreatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Acute chlocystitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
