  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Disclosure is non-negotiable; autonomy transcends prognosis.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is to inform the patient about the retained surgical clamp. Even in terminal illness, patients retain the right to full disclosure regarding their medical care and any complications, enabling them to make informed decisions about their remaining life and treatment options.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThis scenario underscores the paramount importance of patient autonomy and the ethical obligation of medical professionals to disclose all relevant information, including surgical errors or complications. Full transparency fosters trust and allows the patient, in consultation with their care team, to weigh the risks and benefits of potential interventions (like surgery to remove the clamp) against their quality of life and end-of-life wishes, regardless of their prognosis. The decision to operate is secondary to the duty to inform.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"Don’t inform her because she is terminal\" violates fundamental ethical principles of patient autonomy, informed consent, and professional transparency. A patient's terminal status does not negate their right to know about their medical condition or complications.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Principle | Terminal Patient | Non-Terminal Patient | Retained Surgical Item |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Duty to Inform** | Absolute | Absolute | Absolute |\n| **Shared Decision-Making** | Crucial, considering quality of life and end-of-life wishes | Standard of care | Essential for management plan |\n| **Intervention Goal** | Often palliative, symptom management, patient preference | Cure, functional improvement | Removal, complication prevention |\n| **Ethical Imperative** | Respect autonomy, maintain trust | Beneficence, non-maleficence | Transparency, accountability |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always inform the patient of complications; terminal status does not negate autonomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA retained surgical clamp would typically appear as a high-density metallic object on plain radiographs (X-ray) or computed tomography (CT) scans, often with characteristic shapes (e.g., curved jaws, handles). Intraoperatively, it would be a foreign body requiring careful dissection for removal.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Statement on Principles of Patient Safety (2017). This guideline emphasizes transparent communication with patients regarding adverse events and patient safety.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Don’t inform her because she is terminal | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Inform her and refer her surgery | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
