  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When diverticulitis strikes, CT's the sight!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is CT. A CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis with intravenous contrast is the gold standard for diagnosing acute diverticulitis due to its high sensitivity and specificity in identifying inflammation, complications, and ruling out other conditions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCT imaging provides detailed cross-sectional views, allowing for precise identification of colonic wall thickening, pericolic fat stranding, and the presence of complications such as abscess formation, perforation, or fistula. It can also differentiate diverticulitis from other acute abdominal pathologies like appendicitis, inflammatory bowel disease, or gynecological conditions, guiding appropriate management and avoiding unnecessary interventions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Barium enema) (Incorrect): Barium enema is contraindicated in acute diverticulitis due to the risk of perforation and peritonitis from barium extravasation. It is used for evaluating chronic diverticular disease after the acute phase has resolved.\nOption C (colonoscopy) (Incorrect): Colonoscopy is contraindicated in acute diverticulitis due to the significant risk of perforation of the inflamed colon. It is typically performed 6-8 weeks after resolution of an acute episode to rule out malignancy or other colonic pathology.\nOption D (sigmoidoscopy) (Incorrect): Similar to colonoscopy, sigmoidoscopy is generally avoided in acute diverticulitis due to the risk of perforation. It offers limited diagnostic value in the acute setting compared to CT.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Diagnostic Tool | Indication in Diverticular Disease | Contraindication in Acute Diverticulitis | Key Findings |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| CT Abdomen/Pelvis | Acute diverticulitis (gold standard), complications | None | Wall thickening, fat stranding, abscess, perforation |\n| Colonoscopy | Post-acute phase (6-8 weeks), screening, chronic disease | Yes (perforation risk) | Diverticula, polyps, malignancy |\n| Barium Enema | Chronic diverticular disease, post-acute phase | Yes (perforation risk) | Diverticula, strictures, fistulas |\n| Ultrasound | Initial screening, follow-up, less sensitive | None (operator dependent) | Wall thickening, fluid collections |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: CT is the definitive diagnostic tool for acute diverticulitis, ruling out complications and mimics.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, acute diverticulitis typically presents as focal colonic wall thickening (>4mm), pericolic fat stranding, and often the presence of diverticula. Complications like abscesses appear as fluid collections, and perforation may show free air or fluid.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) 2014 guidelines recommend CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis with IV contrast as the diagnostic imaging modality of choice for acute diverticulitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CT | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Barium enema | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | colonoscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | sigmoidoscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
