  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the right lower quadrant screams, think appendix!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption E is the most diagnostic finding for appendicitis. The presence of right lower quadrant tenderness, particularly with rebound, is a hallmark physical examination sign indicating localized peritoneal inflammation, which is highly suggestive of appendicitis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAppendicitis typically begins with vague periumbilical pain that migrates to the right lower quadrant (RLQ) as the inflammation involves the parietal peritoneum. This localized inflammation causes tenderness at McBurney's point, which is approximately one-third of the way from the anterior superior iliac spine to the umbilicus. Rebound tenderness signifies peritoneal irritation, where pain is worse upon rapid release of pressure, indicating inflammation of the peritoneal lining. These findings are crucial for clinical diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Fever is a common systemic response to inflammation but is non-specific and can be present in numerous conditions. It often develops later in appendicitis.\nOption B (Incorrect): Diarrhea is an atypical symptom for appendicitis and is more commonly associated with gastroenteritis or other bowel pathologies. While some patients may experience altered bowel habits, it's not a primary diagnostic feature.\nOption C (Incorrect): Urinary symptoms can occur if an inflamed appendix irritates the bladder or ureter, but they are not direct indicators of appendicitis and are more suggestive of urinary tract infections or renal calculi.\nOption D (Incorrect): Leukocytosis (elevated white blood cell count) is a common laboratory finding in appendicitis, indicating an inflammatory response. However, it is not specific to appendicitis and can be elevated in many other infectious or inflammatory conditions. It is a supportive lab finding, not a primary diagnostic physical sign.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Diagnostic Feature | Description | Specificity |\n|---|---|---|\n| **RLQ Tenderness/Rebound** | Localized pain at McBurney's point, worsened by release of pressure | High |\n| Migratory Pain | Periumbilical pain shifting to RLQ | Moderate |\n| Leukocytosis | Elevated WBC count (>10,000/µL) | Low-Moderate (supportive) |\n| Anorexia/Nausea/Vomiting | Common initial symptoms | Low (non-specific) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: RLQ tenderness with rebound is the classic clinical sign.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, an inflamed appendix appears as a dilated, non-compressible, fluid-filled tubular structure with wall thickening and periappendiceal fat stranding. Intraoperatively, a red, edematous, and often purulent appendix will be observed, sometimes with surrounding fluid or abscess formation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Appendicitis (2020) recommend clinical assessment combined with imaging (ultrasound or CT) for diagnosis, with physical exam findings being paramount.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Fever | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Diarrhea | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Urinary symptoms | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Leukocytosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Tender right lower quadrant with rebound | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
