  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When obturator and psoas signs are positive, think appendix.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe presence of positive obturator and psoas signs strongly indicates an inflammatory process involving the appendix, particularly when it is retrocecal or pelvic in location. These signs reflect irritation of adjacent muscles by the inflamed appendix.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe obturator sign is elicited by internally rotating the right hip with the hip and knee flexed, causing pain if an inflamed appendix is in contact with the obturator internus muscle. The psoas sign is elicited by passively extending the right hip or actively flexing the right hip against resistance, causing pain if an inflamed appendix irritates the psoas major muscle, often seen in retrocecal appendicitis. These specific signs are crucial for localizing inflammation to the right lower quadrant and specifically to the appendix.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Acute cholecystitis typically presents with right upper quadrant pain, Murphy's sign, and systemic inflammatory response, without involvement of the obturator or psoas muscles. The pain is localized to the gallbladder, not the deep pelvic or retroperitoneal structures.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Sign | Appendicitis | Acute Cholecystitis | Anatomical Basis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Obturator Sign | Often positive (pelvic appendix) | Negative | Irritation of obturator internus muscle |\n| Psoas Sign | Often positive (retrocecal appendix) | Negative | Irritation of psoas major muscle |\n| Murphy's Sign | Negative | Often positive | Inflammation of gallbladder |\n| Location of Pain | Right lower quadrant | Right upper quadrant | Appendix vs. Gallbladder |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Obturator and psoas signs point to appendicitis, especially retrocecal or pelvic.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a dilated appendix (>6mm) with wall thickening, periappendiceal fat stranding, and possibly an appendicolith. Intraoperatively, a red, edematous, or gangrenous appendix, often retrocecal or pelvic, with surrounding inflammatory exudate.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) and Society for Surgery of the Alimentary Tract (SSAT) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Appendicitis (2020) recommend imaging (CT or ultrasound) for diagnosis and surgical intervention for confirmed cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Appendicitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Acute cholcysitits | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
