  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't 'morph' the bile flow; choose pain relief wisely!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Morphine. Morphine has historically been considered relatively contraindicated in acute cholecystitis due to its potential to induce spasm of the sphincter of Oddi, which could theoretically worsen biliary obstruction and pain.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute cholecystitis is inflammation of the gallbladder, often caused by gallstone obstruction of the cystic duct. Pain management is crucial, but certain medications can exacerbate the condition. Morphine, a mu-opioid receptor agonist, can cause contraction of smooth muscle, including the sphincter of Oddi. This spasm can increase intraductal pressure in the biliary tree, potentially worsening the obstruction and pain associated with acute cholecystitis. While the clinical significance of this effect is debated and often transient, it remains a classic teaching point in surgical education.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Naproxen) (Incorrect): NSAIDs like naproxen are often used in acute cholecystitis for pain and inflammation control and are not contraindicated unless other patient-specific factors exist.\nOption B (Acetaminophen) (Incorrect): Acetaminophen is a safe and effective analgesic for pain relief in acute cholecystitis and does not affect biliary dynamics.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Drug Class | Example | Effect on Biliary System | Use in Acute Cholecystitis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Opioid Analgesic | Morphine | Sphincter of Oddi spasm (classic teaching) | Relative contraindication, use with caution or alternative |\n| NSAID | Naproxen | Minimal direct effect | Often used for pain and inflammation |\n| Non-opioid Analgesic | Acetaminophen | No direct effect | Safe and effective for pain |\n| Opioid Analgesic (alternative) | Meperidine | Less sphincter spasm than morphine (historically thought) | Historically preferred over morphine, but now less common due to neurotoxicity concerns |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Morphine can spasm the sphincter of Oddi, worsening cholecystitis pain.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, acute cholecystitis typically shows gallbladder wall thickening (>3mm), pericholecystic fluid, gallstones, and a positive sonographic Murphy's sign. Intraoperatively, the gallbladder would appear inflamed, edematous, and potentially distended.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 for the management of acute cholecystitis. These guidelines discuss pain management but do not explicitly contraindicate morphine, acknowledging the debate around sphincter of Oddi spasm.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Naproxen | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Acetaminophen | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Morphine | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
