  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 No stones, big trouble: Acalculous cholecystitis hits the critically ill hardest.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption D is the correct answer. Acalculous cholecystitis is a severe inflammatory condition of the gallbladder that typically arises in critically ill patients, often following major trauma, burns, or extensive surgical procedures.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcalculous cholecystitis is characterized by gallbladder inflammation without the presence of gallstones. Its pathogenesis is multifactorial, involving gallbladder stasis, ischemia, reperfusion injury, and systemic inflammatory responses common in critically ill states. The impaired contractility and bile flow, often exacerbated by prolonged fasting, TPN, and opioid use, lead to bile inspissation, increased intraluminal pressure, and ultimately, inflammation and necrosis of the gallbladder wall. This makes it a distinct entity from calculous cholecystitis, which is primarily caused by cystic duct obstruction by a stone.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Acalculous cholecystitis, by definition, means inflammation of the gallbladder without stones. Association with common bile duct stones would imply calculous disease.\nOption B (Incorrect): Acalculous cholecystitis accounts for 5-10% of all acute cholecystitis cases, not less than 1%. It is a significant minority but not exceedingly rare.\nOption C (Incorrect): Acalculous cholecystitis has a significantly worse prognosis than calculous cholecystitis, with higher morbidity and mortality rates (10-50%) due to the underlying critical illness of the patients.\nOption E (Incorrect): A HIDA scan in acute cholecystitis (calculous or acalculous) typically shows non-filling of the gallbladder due to cystic duct obstruction or severe inflammation, preventing tracer entry.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Calculous Cholecystitis | Acalculous Cholecystitis |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Etiology** | Gallstones obstructing cystic duct | Gallbladder stasis, ischemia, critical illness (trauma, burns, sepsis, major surgery, TPN) |\n| **Patient Population** | Generally healthy, often ambulatory | Critically ill, intubated, post-trauma/surgery, immunosuppressed |\n| **Prognosis** | Generally good with timely treatment | Worse prognosis, higher morbidity/mortality due to underlying conditions |\n| **Diagnosis (HIDA)** | Non-filling of gallbladder | Non-filling of gallbladder |\n| **Treatment** | Cholecystectomy | Cholecystectomy or percutaneous cholecystostomy (often initial management) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acalculous cholecystitis = critically ill + no stones + worse prognosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, findings suggestive of acalculous cholecystitis include gallbladder wall thickening (>3-4mm), pericholecystic fluid, sonographic Murphy's sign (if patient is responsive), and sludge, without evidence of stones. A HIDA scan showing non-filling of the gallbladder after 4 hours is highly diagnostic. Intraoperatively, the gallbladder may appear distended, edematous, necrotic, or gangrenous.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 for the management of acute cholecystitis. These guidelines provide diagnostic criteria and management strategies for both calculous and acalculous cholecystitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It is usually associated with stones in the common bile duct. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It occurs in less than 1% of cases of cholecystitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It has a more favorable prognosis than calculouscholecystitis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | It occurs after trauma or operation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | HIDA scan shows filling gallbladder | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
