  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fiber: The first line of defense against silent hemorrhoids.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is to increase fiber in the diet. For asymptomatic, non-prolapsing internal hemorrhoids (Grade I), conservative management focusing on lifestyle modification is the cornerstone of treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInternal hemorrhoids are normal vascular cushions that become symptomatic when engorged, prolapsed, or thrombosed. In the absence of symptoms like pain, bleeding, or prolapse, the primary goal is to prevent these complications. Increasing dietary fiber helps to soften stool, increase stool bulk, and reduce straining during defecation. This minimizes pressure on the hemorrhoidal cushions, preventing their enlargement, prolapse, and potential thrombosis, thereby addressing the underlying mechanical factors contributing to hemorrhoid development and progression.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Give laxative) (Incorrect): While laxatives can help with constipation, increasing dietary fiber is generally preferred as a first-line, more natural, and sustainable approach for long-term management of hemorrhoids. Laxatives might be considered if fiber alone is insufficient.\nOption C (Do hemorrhoidectomy) (Incorrect): Hemorrhoidectomy is a surgical procedure reserved for symptomatic, higher-grade hemorrhoids (typically Grade III, IV, or severe Grade II refractory to other treatments). It is a highly invasive intervention and completely inappropriate for asymptomatic Grade I internal hemorrhoids.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hemorrhoid Grade | Description | Typical Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| Grade I | Bleeds, but does not prolapse | Conservative (fiber, fluids, lifestyle) |\n| Grade II | Prolapses with defecation, spontaneously reduces | Conservative, rubber band ligation, infrared coagulation |\n| Grade III | Prolapses with defecation, requires manual reduction | Rubber band ligation, hemorrhoidectomy |\n| Grade IV | Prolapsed and irreducible | Hemorrhoidectomy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Asymptomatic Grade I hemorrhoids = fiber first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn anoscopy, a Grade I internal hemorrhoid appears as an enlarged, non-prolapsing vascular cushion within the anal canal, typically above the dentate line. It may appear congested or slightly bluish but does not extend outside the anus.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Hemorrhoids (2018) recommend conservative management, including dietary fiber and fluid intake, as first-line therapy for Grade I and II hemorrhoids.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Increase fiber diet | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Give laxative | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Do hemorroidectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
