  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hemorrhoids: The intermittent red flag of the rectum.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nHemorrhoids are the most common cause of chronic, interrupted rectal bleeding. This is due to their high prevalence and characteristic presentation of bright red blood per rectum, often associated with defecation, which tends to be intermittent.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHemorrhoids are normal vascular cushions within the anal canal that become symptomatic when they enlarge, prolapse, or bleed. During defecation, especially with straining, these engorged vessels can be traumatized, leading to bleeding. The blood is typically bright red, seen on toilet paper, in the toilet bowl, or streaking the stool. The bleeding is characteristically intermittent, often resolving spontaneously only to recur with subsequent bowel movements or increased intra-abdominal pressure, making them the leading cause of chronic, interrupted rectal bleeding.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Diverticulosis typically presents with acute, painless, and often massive lower gastrointestinal bleeding, rather than chronic and interrupted bleeding. While it is a common cause of lower GI bleeding, its presentation differs significantly from the pattern described.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hemorrhoids | Diverticulosis |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Bleeding Pattern** | Chronic, intermittent, bright red | Acute, often massive, painless |\n| **Associated Symptoms** | Pain (if thrombosed), itching, prolapse | Usually asymptomatic until bleeding |\n| **Location** | Anorectal junction | Colon (usually left, but right in Asian populations) |\n| **Diagnosis** | Anoscopy, proctoscopy | Colonoscopy, CT angiography (for active bleed) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bright red, intermittent rectal bleeding? Think hemorrhoids first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn anoscopy or proctoscopy, engorged, often prolapsing vascular cushions will be directly visualized in the anal canal. Bleeding may be seen actively or evidence of prior bleeding (e.g., clots, friable mucosa).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Hemorrhoids (2018). These guidelines provide evidence-based recommendations for the diagnosis and treatment of hemorrhoidal disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Diverticulosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hemorrhoids | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
