  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hemorrhoids: Know your anatomy, save your patient's posterior.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption B is correct because internal hemorrhoids, which are the most common type to cause symptomatic issues like bleeding, are indeed supplied by branches of the superior rectal artery. This is a fundamental anatomical fact crucial for understanding hemorrhoidal disease.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHemorrhoids are normal vascular cushions in the anal canal. Internal hemorrhoids are located above the dentate line and are supplied by the superior rectal artery, a terminal branch of the inferior mesenteric artery. These are covered by columnar epithelium and have visceral innervation, making them typically painless unless prolapsed or thrombosed. External hemorrhoids, located below the dentate line, are supplied by the inferior rectal artery (a branch of the internal pudendal artery) and are covered by anoderm with somatic innervation, making them highly sensitive to pain.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Hemorrhoids are not usually due to cirrhosis. While portal hypertension from cirrhosis can lead to anorectal varices, these are distinct from true hemorrhoids, which are normal vascular cushions that become symptomatic due to straining, constipation, or pregnancy.\nOption C (Incorrect): A high-bulk diet is generally recommended to prevent hemorrhoids by promoting soft stools and reducing straining. A low-bulk diet leading to constipation is more commonly associated with their development.\nOption D (Incorrect): While hemorrhoids can be a source of pain (especially if thrombosed or significantly prolapsed) and pruritus (assuming 'purities' is a typo for pruritus), bleeding is the most common symptom of internal hemorrhoids, which are often painless. Pain is more characteristic of thrombosed external hemorrhoids.\nOption E (Incorrect): While chronic bleeding from hemorrhoids can lead to iron deficiency anemia, it is a potential complication, not a usual association. Many individuals have hemorrhoids without developing anemia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Internal Hemorrhoids | External Hemorrhoids |\n|---|---|---|\n| Location | Proximal to dentate line | Distal to dentate line |\n| Nerve Supply | Visceral (painless) | Somatic (painful) |\n| Arterial Supply | Superior rectal artery | Inferior rectal artery |\n| Common Symptoms | Painless bleeding, prolapse | Pain (especially if thrombosed), swelling |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Internal hemorrhoids are painless, bleed, and get superior rectal artery supply.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn anoscopy or proctoscopy, internal hemorrhoids appear as reddish-purple, bulging vascular cushions in the anal canal, typically at the 3, 7, and 11 o'clock positions in the lithotomy position.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Hemorrhoids (2018) recommend a fiber-rich diet and conservative management for early-stage hemorrhoids.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Usually due to cirrhosis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Attributed to branches of superior hemorrhoidal artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Due to high bulk diet. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | A source of pain and purities. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Usually associated with anemia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
