  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pulsatile mass? US it, before it's too late!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is US. A pulsatile abdominal mass is highly suspicious for an abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA), and ultrasound is the most appropriate initial diagnostic study due to its speed, non-invasiveness, and cost-effectiveness.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUltrasound is the gold standard for screening and initial diagnosis of abdominal aortic aneurysms. It provides real-time imaging, allowing for rapid assessment of aortic diameter, presence of thrombus, and potential signs of rupture, all without radiation exposure or intravenous contrast. Its portability and relatively low cost make it an ideal first-line investigation in an emergent or outpatient setting for a suspected AAA.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (MRI): Incorrect. While MRI can provide detailed anatomical information, it is more expensive, less readily available, and takes significantly longer than ultrasound. It is typically reserved for more complex cases, pre-operative planning when CT is contraindicated, or when ultrasound is inconclusive, not as the initial diagnostic step for a suspected AAA.\nOption A (US): Correct. Ultrasound is the initial diagnostic test of choice for a pulsatile abdominal mass due to its non-invasiveness, cost-effectiveness, and ability to rapidly confirm or rule out an abdominal aortic aneurysm.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Primary Use | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Ultrasound (US)** | Screening, initial diagnosis, surveillance of AAA | Non-invasive, no radiation, cost-effective, portable, real-time | Operator-dependent, limited by bowel gas/obesity |\n| **CT Angiography (CTA)** | Pre-operative planning, rupture assessment, complex anatomy | Detailed anatomy, rapid, good for rupture | Radiation exposure, contrast nephropathy risk |\n| **MRI/MRA** | Pre-operative planning (if CT contraindicated), detailed wall assessment | No radiation, good soft tissue contrast | Expensive, time-consuming, contraindications (pacemakers) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pulsatile abdominal mass? Think AAA, first test is US.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a pulsatile abdominal mass suspicious for AAA would show an aortic diameter greater than 3 cm, often with mural thrombus. Signs of rupture might include retroperitoneal fluid or hematoma.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Society for Vascular Surgery (SVS) 2018 Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Abdominal Aortic Aneurysms recommend ultrasound as the primary screening and surveillance tool for AAA.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | US | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | MRI | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
