  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Early facial suture removal: less track, more beauty.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question addresses the critical timing for facial suture removal. While the ideal range is 4-7 days, option B (3-5 days) is the closest and most appropriate choice among the given options, emphasizing early removal to optimize cosmetic outcomes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFacial skin is highly vascularized, leading to rapid wound healing. Early suture removal, typically within 4-7 days, is crucial to prevent epithelialization into the suture tracts, which causes unsightly 'track marks' or 'railroad tracks.' This timing balances sufficient wound tensile strength with minimizing foreign body reaction and scarring, ensuring the best possible cosmetic result.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Using absorbable sutures for superficial skin closure on the face is generally incorrect. While absorbable sutures are used subcutaneously, non-absorbable sutures are preferred for skin approximation to achieve precise closure and are then removed. Leaving absorbable sutures on the surface can lead to inflammation, delayed healing, and increased scarring.\nOption B (Incorrect, but closest): While 3-5 days is on the earlier side, it falls within the acceptable window (4-7 days) for facial suture removal and is the best choice among the given options. Removing sutures too early risks wound dehiscence, but facial wounds heal quickly.\nOption C (Incorrect): Two weeks is far too long for facial sutures. Leaving sutures in for this duration will almost certainly result in prominent track marks and increased scarring due to the skin growing into the suture material.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Body Region | Suture Removal Time | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Face/Neck | 4-7 days | Rapid healing, minimize scarring/track marks |\n| Scalp/Trunk | 7-10 days | Moderate healing, good tensile strength |\n| Extremities | 10-14 days | Slower healing, higher tension |\n| Joints/Back | 14-21 days | High tension, prolonged healing, often non-absorbable deep sutures |\n| Eyelids | 3-5 days | Very thin skin, rapid healing, high cosmetic concern |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Facial sutures: 4-7 days to prevent track marks and ensure cosmetic excellence.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, meticulous skin edge eversion and tension-free closure are paramount on the face. The goal is to achieve primary intention healing with minimal inflammation, which facilitates early suture removal and optimal scar appearance. No specific imaging is typically used for suture removal timing.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Wound Care Guidelines (various years) and general plastic surgery principles advocate for early suture removal in cosmetically sensitive areas like the face to minimize scarring.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | U should use absorbable suture | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 3 to 5 Days | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 2 weeks | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) The ideal is between 4-7 days.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
