  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, scope it out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. ERCP is the correct answer because it offers both definitive diagnosis and therapeutic intervention for common bile duct obstruction, making it superior to ultrasound for precise identification and management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nERCP (Endoscopic Retrograde Cholangiopancreatography) provides direct visualization of the ampulla and allows for cannulation of the bile duct to perform cholangiography. This enables precise identification of the location, nature (e.g., stone, stricture, tumor), and extent of the obstruction. Furthermore, ERCP can immediately proceed to therapeutic interventions like stone extraction, sphincterotomy, or stent placement, which ultrasound cannot.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Ultrasound (US) is an excellent initial screening tool for obstructive jaundice, often showing dilated bile ducts, but it is operator-dependent and less sensitive for definitively identifying the cause or exact location of a distal common bile duct obstruction, especially small stones or subtle strictures.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Role | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| US | Initial screening | Non-invasive, readily available, inexpensive, detects ductal dilation | Operator-dependent, poor sensitivity for distal CBD, no therapeutic capability |\n| CT | Further evaluation, rule out mass | Good for pancreatic head masses, defines anatomy | Radiation exposure, limited sensitivity for small CBD stones, no therapeutic capability |\n| MRCP | Non-invasive cholangiography | No radiation, excellent visualization of biliary tree, non-invasive | No therapeutic capability, limited availability, can overestimate obstruction |\n| ERCP | Diagnostic and therapeutic | Gold standard for diagnosis, allows intervention (stone removal, stenting) | Invasive, risk of pancreatitis, perforation, bleeding, radiation exposure |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: ERCP is the definitive diagnostic and therapeutic tool for CBD obstruction.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ERCP, a common bile duct obstruction would appear as a filling defect (e.g., stone), a focal narrowing (stricture), or an abrupt cutoff of contrast flow, often with upstream ductal dilation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Gastrointestinal Endoscopy (ASGE) Guideline 2019: The Role of Endoscopy in the Management of Choledocholithiasis. It recommends ERCP for patients with high probability of choledocholithiasis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | ERCP | ✅ Correct |\n| B | US | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ERCP** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
