  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Tongue out, cyst up: it's a thyroglossal hiccup!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B - Thyroglossal Cyst. This diagnosis is confirmed by the classic clinical sign of a midline neck swelling that elevates with tongue protrusion, indicating its embryological connection to the tongue base.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThyroglossal cysts arise from remnants of the thyroglossal duct, which is the embryonic tract through which the thyroid gland descends from the foramen cecum at the base of the tongue to its final position in the neck. This duct normally atrophies, but if portions persist, they can form cysts. The duct often passes through or is intimately associated with the hyoid bone. Therefore, when the tongue is protruded, the hyoid bone elevates, pulling the cyst superiorly, making this a pathognomonic sign.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Goiter) (Incorrect): A goiter is an enlargement of the thyroid gland, typically located lower in the neck, and does not characteristically move with tongue protrusion. Its movement is usually with swallowing.\nOption C (Cystic Hygroma) (Incorrect): A cystic hygroma is a lymphatic malformation, usually found in the lateral neck or supraclavicular region, and does not move with tongue protrusion. It is typically soft, compressible, and transilluminates.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Thyroglossal Cyst | Goiter | Cystic Hygroma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Location** | Midline neck, often near hyoid bone | Anterior neck, lower, bilateral or unilateral | Lateral neck, supraclavicular, posterior triangle |\n| **Movement with Tongue Protrusion** | Yes, classic sign | No | No |\n| **Movement with Swallowing** | Yes | Yes | No |\n| **Etiology** | Remnant of thyroglossal duct | Thyroid gland enlargement (e.g., iodine deficiency, autoimmune) | Lymphatic malformation |\n| **Consistency** | Smooth, firm, cystic | Firm, variable | Soft, compressible, transilluminates |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Midline neck mass + tongue protrusion = Thyroglossal Cyst.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or CT, a thyroglossal cyst appears as a well-defined, anechoic or hypoechoic midline cystic lesion, often superior to the thyroid gland. Intraoperatively, the Sistrunk procedure involves excising the cyst, the central portion of the hyoid bone, and a core of muscle tissue up to the foramen cecum to prevent recurrence.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) guidelines for pediatric neck masses recommend surgical excision (Sistrunk procedure) for symptomatic or infected thyroglossal duct cysts.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Goiter | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Thyroglossal Cyst | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Cystic Hygroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Thyroglossal Cyst** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
