  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When limbs lack flow, vascular surgeons know where to go!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The correct answer is Vascular surgery. A patient presenting with lower limb ischemia, even with a history of heart disease, requires specialized evaluation and management by a vascular surgeon to assess the extent of arterial compromise and determine the need for revascularization.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLower limb ischemia indicates compromised blood flow to the extremities, often due to peripheral artery disease (PAD). Vascular surgeons are experts in diagnosing and treating PAD through various interventions, including angioplasty, stenting, or bypass surgery. Their expertise is crucial for limb salvage and improving quality of life, especially in patients with cardiac comorbidities who may have diffuse atherosclerotic disease.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Referred to cardiology. While the patient has heart disease, cardiology primarily manages cardiac conditions. Lower limb ischemia is a peripheral vascular issue that falls under the purview of vascular surgery for definitive diagnosis and treatment.\nOption C (Incorrect): Start heparin. Heparin is an anticoagulant used in acute limb ischemia or DVT. The question describes a complaint of ischemia, not necessarily an acute event requiring immediate empiric anticoagulation without a full vascular workup. It's not the primary 'advice' for initial management.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Primary Specialty | Initial Diagnostic Workup | Definitive Treatment |\n| :----------------------- | :---------------- | :------------------------ | :------------------- |\n| **Lower Limb Ischemia** | Vascular Surgery | Ankle-Brachial Index (ABI), Duplex US, CTA/MRA | Revascularization (Endovascular/Open) |\n| **Acute Coronary Syndrome** | Cardiology | ECG, Troponins, Cardiac Catheterization | PCI/CABG |\n| **Deep Vein Thrombosis** | Internal Medicine/Vascular | Duplex US | Anticoagulation, +/- Thrombolysis |\n| **Claudication** | Vascular Surgery | ABI, Exercise Testing | Risk factor modification, Supervised exercise, +/- Revascularization |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ischemia below the diaphragm? Think vascular surgery.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDiagnostic imaging for lower limb ischemia typically includes duplex ultrasound, CT angiography (CTA), or MR angiography (MRA) to identify the location and severity of arterial stenoses or occlusions. In the OR, one might see significant atherosclerotic plaques, thrombus, or complete arterial occlusion requiring endarterectomy or bypass grafting.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2016 AHA/ACC Guideline on the Management of Patients With Lower Extremity Peripheral Artery Disease. Recommends comprehensive evaluation and risk factor modification, with revascularization for lifestyle-limiting claudication or critical limb ischemia.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Referred to cardiology | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Vascular surgery | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Start heparin | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Vascular surgery** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
