  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For pediatric duodenal hematomas, watchful waiting often wins.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nObservation is the correct management for a child with a duodenal hematoma following blunt abdominal trauma, assuming the patient is hemodynamically stable. Intramural duodenal hematomas in children typically resolve spontaneously with non-operative management, avoiding the risks associated with surgical intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe duodenum, despite its retroperitoneal location, has a rich blood supply that facilitates the resorption of intramural hematomas. Non-operative management, involving bowel rest (NPO), nasogastric decompression, and intravenous fluids, allows the body's natural processes to resolve the hematoma. This approach is highly successful in pediatric patients, preventing the morbidity associated with surgery while achieving complete resolution of the obstruction and hematoma.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Ct guided evacuation of Hematoma) (Incorrect): CT-guided evacuation is generally not indicated for intramural duodenal hematomas due to the risk of iatrogenic injury to the duodenum or surrounding structures, and the high success rate of non-operative management.\nOption B (Explorative laparotomy and evacuation of hematoma) (Incorrect): Explorative laparotomy is an overly aggressive approach for an isolated duodenal hematoma in a stable child. It carries significant surgical risks and is reserved for cases of perforation, ongoing hemorrhage, complete bowel obstruction unresponsive to conservative measures, or failure of non-operative management.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Management Strategy | Indication | Outcome |\n|---|---|---|\n| Observation (Non-operative) | Stable patient, isolated intramural hematoma, no perforation/active bleed | High success rate, spontaneous resolution, avoids surgery |\n| CT-guided evacuation | Rarely indicated for intramural hematoma; higher risk than benefit | Potential for iatrogenic injury, not standard of care |\n| Explorative laparotomy | Perforation, active hemorrhage, complete bowel obstruction, failure of non-op management | Invasive, higher morbidity, definitive repair |\n| Endoscopic drainage | Rarely used, potential for perforation, not first-line for hematoma | Limited role, usually for specific obstructive cases |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Stable pediatric duodenal hematoma? Observe and support.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT imaging, a duodenal hematoma typically appears as a C-shaped or crescentic intramural thickening of the duodenal wall, often causing luminal narrowing and a 'coiled spring' appearance of the mucosa. The hematoma itself may show high-attenuation fluid within the wall.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Pediatric Surgical Association (APSA) Guidelines for the Management of Pediatric Blunt Abdominal Trauma (2019) recommend non-operative management for most blunt abdominal injuries in stable children, including isolated intramural duodenal hematomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ct guided evacuation of Hematoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Explorative laparotomy and evacuation of hematoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Observation | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Observation** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
