  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When amoeba's in the liver, metronidazole's the giver!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct diagnosis is Amoebic liver abscess. This is unequivocally indicated by the patient's symptoms of right upper quadrant pain, fever, and tender hepatomegaly, coupled with the critical finding of a positive amoeba investigation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAmoebic liver abscess (ALA) is caused by Entamoeba histolytica, typically acquired through ingestion of contaminated food or water. Trophozoites invade the colonic mucosa, enter the portal circulation, and establish infection in the liver, forming characteristic 'anchovy paste' pus. The clinical presentation often mimics other liver abscesses, but the definitive diagnosis hinges on serological tests for E. histolytica antibodies or direct identification of amoebic trophozoites, as highlighted by the 'positive amoeba' finding in this case.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Pyogenic liver abscess is caused by bacterial infection, often polymicrobial, and would not be associated with a 'positive amoeba' investigation. While symptoms can overlap, the etiology is distinct.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Amoebic Liver Abscess | Pyogenic Liver Abscess |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Etiology** | Entamoeba histolytica | Bacterial (e.g., E. coli, Klebsiella, Streptococcus) |\n| **Risk Factors** | Endemic areas, poor sanitation | Biliary tract disease, appendicitis, diverticulitis, sepsis |\n| **Pus Character** | 'Anchovy paste' (sterile) | Thick, foul-smelling (purulent) |\n| **Diagnosis** | Serology (E. histolytica antibodies), stool/abscess aspirate for trophozoites | Blood cultures, abscess aspirate culture |\n| **Treatment** | Metronidazole, followed by luminal amoebicide | Antibiotics, percutaneous drainage |\n| **Imaging** | Typically single, peripheral, well-defined | Often multiple, central, ill-defined |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Positive amoeba + liver abscess symptoms = Amoebic liver abscess.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or CT, an amoebic liver abscess typically appears as a solitary, well-defined, hypoechoic or hypodense lesion, often in the right lobe, without significant internal septations. It may have a peripheral rim enhancement on contrast-enhanced CT. Aspiration, if performed, yields characteristic 'anchovy paste' pus, which is usually sterile on bacterial culture.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInfectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) 2017 Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Amebiasis: Recommends metronidazole as the primary treatment for amoebic liver abscess, followed by a luminal agent.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pyogenic liver abscess | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Amoebic liver abscess. | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Amoebic liver abscess.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
