  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 No food, no full insulin dose; prevent the hypo, keep the patient safe.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D because a fasting diabetic patient undergoing elective surgery is at high risk for hypoglycemia if their usual insulin dose is administered. Omitting the scheduled dose and managing glucose with a sliding scale insulin infusion is the safest approach to prevent perioperative complications.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuring fasting, the body's glucose production from the liver (gluconeogenesis and glycogenolysis) continues, but exogenous glucose intake ceases. Administering a patient's usual insulin dose, especially long-acting or pre-meal insulin, without corresponding carbohydrate intake, will lead to a significant drop in blood glucose levels. Hypoglycemia is a dangerous perioperative complication, potentially causing neurological damage, cardiac arrhythmias, and delayed awakening. A sliding scale insulin regimen allows for dynamic adjustment of insulin based on real-time blood glucose measurements, providing tight control while minimizing the risk of hypoglycemia in the absence of oral intake.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Giving even a half dose of morning insulin to a fasting patient still carries a substantial risk of hypoglycemia, as there is no carbohydrate intake to counteract its effect.\nOption B (Incorrect): Administering half doses of both morning and midnight insulin is even more dangerous, as it compounds the risk of hypoglycemia over an extended period without food.\nOption C (Incorrect): Giving the usual insulin dose to a fasting patient is highly inappropriate and would almost certainly lead to severe hypoglycemia, a life-threatening complication.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Scenario | Insulin Management |\n|---|---|\n| Type 1 DM, Fasting, Elective Surgery | Basal insulin reduced (e.g., 50-75%), bolus omitted. IV dextrose + sliding scale. |\n| Type 2 DM, Fasting, Elective Surgery | Oral hypoglycemics held. Basal insulin reduced/omitted. Sliding scale. |\n| DM, Non-fasting, Minor Procedure | May take usual insulin/oral meds if eating. Monitor closely. |\n| DM, Major Surgery, Prolonged Fasting | IV insulin infusion (sliding scale) with dextrose. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Fasting DM patients omit scheduled insulin; manage with sliding scale.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nN/A. This question pertains to perioperative medical management of diabetes, not imaging or specific intraoperative findings.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Diabetes Association (ADA) Standards of Medical Care in Diabetes - 2024. Recommends holding most oral hypoglycemic agents and non-insulin injectables, and adjusting insulin regimens (often reducing basal insulin and omitting bolus insulin) for fasting patients, with glucose managed by IV insulin infusion or sliding scale.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | half dose of morning dose | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | half dose of morning and half dose of midnight | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | usual insulin dose | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | you will let him omit the scheduled surgery dose | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) you will let him omit the scheduled surgery dose\nwill be on sliding scale in RBS level within normal** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
