  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 DPL: When time is blood, lavage saves lives.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nDiagnostic Peritoneal Lavage (DPL) is a highly sensitive and rapid diagnostic test for intra-abdominal hemorrhage following trauma, particularly critical when a patient's hemodynamic stability is uncertain or compromised, necessitating immediate identification of bleeding.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDPL involves inserting a catheter into the peritoneal cavity and aspirating fluid. A positive aspirate (e.g., gross blood, specific cell counts) indicates significant intra-abdominal injury requiring surgical exploration. Its high sensitivity (approaching 98%) for detecting free blood makes it invaluable for quickly identifying patients who need emergent laparotomy, especially in resource-limited settings or when advanced imaging like CT is not feasible for an unstable patient. This direct assessment of the peritoneal cavity for blood bypasses the time constraints and transport risks associated with CT scans in unstable trauma patients.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): CT scan is the gold standard for detailed abdominal injury assessment in *hemodynamically stable* trauma patients. However, it is contraindicated in unstable patients due to the time required for the scan and the risk associated with transporting an unstable patient away from resuscitation facilities. The question implies a need for the \"most important\" test, which often means the one that guides immediate life-saving intervention, especially if stability is a concern.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Test | Indication | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **DPL** | Unstable trauma, equivocal FAST, when FAST/CT unavailable | Rapid, highly sensitive for blood, can be done in ED | Invasive, non-therapeutic, misses retroperitoneal/diaphragmatic injuries, high false positive rate for non-operative management |\n| **FAST** | Initial assessment for blunt/penetrating trauma, unstable patients | Rapid, non-invasive, repeatable, can be done at bedside | Operator dependent, limited by body habitus/gas, misses retroperitoneal/bowel injuries, less sensitive than DPL for small bleeds |\n| **CT Scan** | Hemodynamically stable trauma patients | Gold standard for detailed injury assessment, identifies specific organ injuries, retroperitoneal injuries | Time-consuming, radiation exposure, requires patient transport, contraindicated in unstable patients |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unstable trauma + suspected bleed = rapid assessment (FAST/DPL) before CT.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA positive DPL is indicated by gross blood on initial aspiration (>10 mL), or if lavage fluid returns with a red blood cell count >100,000 cells/mm3, white blood cell count >500 cells/mm3, or amylase >175 U/dL. This indicates the need for surgical exploration.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons Committee on Trauma (ACS COT) Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) Guidelines, 11th Edition (2022). ATLS emphasizes rapid assessment and intervention for unstable trauma patients, with DPL being a key diagnostic tool when FAST is unavailable or equivocal, and CT is not an option.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CT scan “if the patient stable” | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Diagnostic peritoneal lavage DPL | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
