  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 DPL: 100k RBCs means go to OR.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption A is the correct answer. A positive diagnostic peritoneal lavage (DPL) is indicated by the presence of more than 100,000 red blood cells per cubic millimeter in the lavage fluid, signifying significant intra-abdominal hemorrhage requiring further intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDiagnostic peritoneal lavage (DPL) is a highly sensitive invasive procedure used to detect intra-abdominal injury in hemodynamically unstable trauma patients when other diagnostic modalities like FAST are unavailable or inconclusive. The presence of a high RBC count, specifically exceeding 100,000 cells/mm³, indicates significant bleeding that often warrants surgical exploration. This threshold is critical as it differentiates minor, clinically insignificant bleeding from hemorrhage requiring intervention. The procedure involves inserting a catheter into the peritoneal cavity and aspirating fluid, or infusing and then draining saline, which is then analyzed for various components.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): 2 ml of gross blood is below the threshold for a positive DPL, which typically requires 10 ml of gross blood aspiration to be considered positive.\nOption C (Incorrect): While DPL criteria can be modified in specific populations like pregnant patients, 2 ml of gross blood is generally not considered a positive finding for significant hemorrhage in any patient.\nOption D (Incorrect): This option describes the clinical utility and indications for performing a DPL, not a criterion for a positive result of the lavage itself. The question asks for indicators of a positive DPL.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Indicator | Positive DPL Threshold |\n|---|---|\n| Gross Blood Aspiration | > 10 mL |\n| Red Blood Cells (RBCs) | > 100,000 cells/mm³ |\n| White Blood Cells (WBCs) | > 500 cells/mm³ |\n| Amylase | > 175 IU/L |\n| Enteric Contents | Presence of bile, bacteria, food fibers, or stool |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: DPL positive if >100k RBCs, >10ml gross blood, or enteric contents.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn FAST (Focused Assessment with Sonography for Trauma), free fluid in the abdomen (pericardial, perihepatic, perisplenic, or pelvic views) would suggest intra-abdominal injury. In the operating room, a positive DPL would lead to a laparotomy where active bleeding, bowel perforation, or other injuries would be directly visualized and repaired.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons Committee on Trauma (ACS COT) Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) 10th Edition (2018) recommends DPL as an option for hemodynamically unstable blunt or penetrating trauma patients with suspected intra-abdominal injury when FAST is unavailable or inconclusive.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 100000 RBCs. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 2 ml gross blood. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 2 ml in pregnant lady. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | DPL is useful for patients who are in shock and when FAST capability is not | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN)  Indicators of positive DPL:\n1) 10ml of blood or enteric contents (stool, food, etc.)\n2) More than ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
