  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Spleen: The fragile king of blunt abdominal trauma.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Spleen. The spleen is the most commonly injured organ in blunt abdominal trauma due to its superficial location, fragile capsule, and rich vascularity, making it highly susceptible to rupture upon impact.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe spleen's anatomical position in the left upper quadrant, protected only by the lower ribs, makes it vulnerable to direct impact or deceleration forces. Its delicate parenchyma and thin capsule are easily disrupted, leading to lacerations or hematomas. Furthermore, its high vascularity means even minor injuries can result in significant hemorrhage, often necessitating intervention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The Liver is the second most commonly injured organ in blunt abdominal trauma, particularly in the right upper quadrant. While frequently affected, its more robust parenchyma and protection by the rib cage make it slightly less vulnerable than the spleen overall.\nOption C (Incorrect): The Kidney is less commonly injured than the spleen or liver in blunt abdominal trauma. Renal injuries typically result from direct flank trauma or deceleration, and while significant, they do not surpass the incidence of splenic injury.\nOption D (Incorrect): The Intestine (small or large bowel) is relatively protected within the abdominal cavity and is less frequently injured in blunt trauma compared to solid organs. Bowel injuries often involve specific mechanisms like seatbelt compression or deceleration tears at fixed points, and their diagnosis can be more challenging.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Organ | Relative Frequency in Blunt Trauma | Typical Injury | Management Approach |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Spleen | Most Common | Laceration, Hematoma, Rupture | Non-operative (most), Splenectomy/Splenorrhaphy |\n| Liver | Second Most Common | Laceration, Hematoma | Non-operative (most), Hepatic resection/Repair |\n| Kidney | Less Common | Contusion, Laceration | Non-operative (most), Nephrectomy/Repair |\n| Bowel | Least Common (Solid Organs) | Perforation, Serosal tear, Mesenteric avulsion | Operative (most) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Spleen is #1 in blunt abdominal trauma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, splenic injuries appear as lacerations (hypodense lines), subcapsular or intraparenchymal hematomas (crescent-shaped or irregular hypodense collections), or active extravasation of contrast (hyperdense blush). Intraoperatively, a ruptured spleen will show active bleeding and parenchymal disruption.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) 10th Edition (2018). ATLS emphasizes rapid assessment and management of blunt abdominal trauma, including focused assessment with sonography for trauma (FAST) and CT imaging for stable patients, with a strong focus on identifying and managing solid organ injuries like splenic rupture.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Liver | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Spleen | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Kidney | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Intestine | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
