  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bilious vomit in an infant? Think twist, don't miss!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Midgut volvulus. This diagnosis is critical in a 2-month-old infant presenting with vomiting after every meal, as it represents an acute surgical emergency that can rapidly lead to bowel ischemia and necrosis if not promptly addressed.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMidgut volvulus occurs when the small bowel, due to an underlying malrotation, twists around the superior mesenteric artery. This twisting obstructs the bowel lumen and, more critically, compromises the blood supply, leading to bilious vomiting (indicating obstruction distal to the ampulla of Vater) and potential bowel gangrene. The infant's age and acute, severe vomiting pattern are highly suggestive of this life-threatening condition, which requires immediate surgical intervention (Ladd's procedure) to untwist the bowel and prevent catastrophic outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Meconium ileus) (Incorrect): Meconium ileus typically presents in the neonatal period with delayed passage of meconium, abdominal distension, and bilious vomiting, often associated with cystic fibrosis. The infant in the question passed meconium early, making this diagnosis unlikely.\nOption C (Hirschsprung disease) (Incorrect): Hirschsprung disease usually presents with chronic constipation, abdominal distension, and delayed passage of meconium. While vomiting can occur, it's typically not the primary symptom after every meal in a 2-month-old who has passed meconium early and passed stool.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Midgut Volvulus | Meconium Ileus | Hirschsprung Disease |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Age of Onset** | Neonatal to infancy (often <1 year) | Neonatal period | Neonatal to infancy/childhood |\n| **Key Symptoms** | Acute bilious vomiting, abdominal pain/distension, shock | Delayed meconium, abdominal distension, bilious vomiting | Chronic constipation, delayed meconium, abdominal distension |\n| **Meconium Passage** | Normal | Delayed/Absent | Delayed |\n| **Pathophysiology** | Malrotation with twisting of bowel around SMA | Obstruction by inspissated meconium (often CF-related) | Aganglionic segment of colon |\n| **Urgency** | Surgical Emergency | Surgical/Medical Management | Surgical Management |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bilious vomiting in an infant is volvulus until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nAn upper GI series showing a 'corkscrew sign' of the duodenum or an absent/abnormal duodenojejunal junction is diagnostic. On ultrasound, the superior mesenteric artery (SMA) and vein (SMV) relationship may be inverted ('whirlpool sign'). Intraoperatively, malrotation with a narrow mesenteric base and twisted bowel loops are observed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Bilious Vomiting in the Neonate (2018): Recommends immediate evaluation for surgical emergencies like malrotation with volvulus in any neonate with bilious emesis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Midgut volvulus | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Meconium ileus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hirschsprung disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
