  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Posterior is primary, lateral is scary.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Posterior. The posterior midline of the anal canal is the most common site for anal fissures due to a combination of anatomical and physiological factors that make it particularly vulnerable to trauma and impaired healing.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAnal fissures are linear tears in the anoderm, overwhelmingly found in the posterior midline (6 o'clock position in lithotomy). This predilection is attributed to the posterior commissure being a watershed area with relatively poor blood supply, making it susceptible to ischemia. Furthermore, the posterior aspect of the internal anal sphincter is often thicker, leading to higher resting pressures and reduced blood flow, which hinders healing. The posterior midline also experiences maximal stretching forces during defecation, contributing to the initial tear.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Anterior fissures are the second most common site, typically occurring in 5-10% of cases, and are more frequently seen in women, sometimes associated with obstetric trauma. They are less common than posterior fissures due to better vascularity and different biomechanical stresses.\nOption C (Incorrect): Lateral fissures are rare, accounting for less than 1% of cases. Their presence is highly atypical for a primary anal fissure and should prompt investigation for secondary causes such as Crohn's disease, tuberculosis, HIV, syphilis, or malignancy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Posterior Fissure | Anterior Fissure | Lateral Fissure |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Prevalence** | Most common (>90%) | Less common (5-10%) | Rare (<1%) |\n| **Etiology** | Primary (trauma, poor blood supply) | Primary (trauma, often in women) | Secondary (Crohn's, infection, malignancy) |\n| **Significance** | Typical, benign | Typical, benign | Atypical, warrants further investigation |\n| **Treatment** | Conservative, LIS | Conservative, LIS | Treat underlying cause |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Posterior fissure is primary; lateral fissure means look for secondary causes.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn digital rectal examination or anoscopy, a linear tear in the anoderm would be visible, typically at the 6 o'clock position (posterior midline). Chronic fissures may present with a sentinel pile distally and a hypertrophied anal papilla proximally.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Anal Fissure (2017). These guidelines recommend conservative management as first-line therapy for acute fissures and surgical options like lateral internal sphincterotomy for chronic, refractory cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Anterior | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Posterior | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Lateral | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
