  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Time is stomach's enemy for lavage success.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption C is correct because gastric lavage is a time-sensitive procedure. For aspirin (ASA) ingestion, significant absorption occurs within a few hours, rendering lavage largely ineffective if performed more than 8 hours post-ingestion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGastric lavage aims to remove unabsorbed toxins from the stomach lumen. Its efficacy is directly dependent on the time elapsed since ingestion, as drugs like aspirin are rapidly absorbed, primarily in the stomach and small intestine. After several hours, most of the ingested substance will have moved beyond the stomach and entered systemic circulation, making mechanical removal from the stomach futile. The rapid absorption kinetics of ASA underscore the critical importance of early intervention for gastric decontamination methods.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While gastric lavage is generally safer than inducing vomiting in a semi-conscious patient due to aspiration risk, the question asks what is 'true about gastric lavage' in a broader sense, and its time-sensitive efficacy (Option C) is a more critical and defining characteristic of its utility.\nOption B (Incorrect): The patient should be in the left lateral decubitus position with the head down (Trendelenburg) to minimize aspiration risk and facilitate lavage. Simply stating 'lateral position' is incomplete and less critical than the time-dependent efficacy.\nOption D (Incorrect): Paraffin oil (mineral oil) is not an indication for gastric lavage. It is sometimes used as a laxative or to aid passage of foreign bodies, but gastric lavage is for removing ingested toxins, not for administering or dealing with paraffin oil in this context.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Intervention | Primary Use | Efficacy Window | Contraindications |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Gastric Lavage | Acute toxin removal | Within 1-2 hours (up to 4-6h for some drugs) | Caustic agents, hydrocarbons, unprotected airway |\n| Activated Charcoal | Adsorption of toxins | Within 1-2 hours | Caustic agents, heavy metals, hydrocarbons, unprotected airway |\n| Whole Bowel Irrigation | Sustained-release drugs, body packers, heavy metals | Up to 6-8 hours or longer | Ileus, bowel obstruction, unprotected airway |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gastric lavage efficacy is time-dependent; early intervention is key.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThe provided images illustrate various aspects of gastric lavage technique and equipment, which would be relevant for understanding the procedure. While not directly an imaging pearl, understanding the physical setup and potential complications (e.g., aspiration) is crucial.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Clinical Toxicology (AACT) and European Association of Poisons Centres and Clinical Toxicologists (EAPCCT) Position Statements on Gastric Lavage (2013) generally recommend against routine use of gastric lavage due to limited evidence of improved outcomes and emphasize its time-sensitive and limited role.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Safer than induce vomiting in semi-conscious pt | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Patient should be in lateral position when you want to do it | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Useless if ASA was ingested >8 hrs | ✅ Correct |\n| D | indicated with paraffin oil | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ![Image](/images/review_bank/467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi_190.jpeg)\n\n\n\n![Image](/images/revie** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
