  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the labia swell, think Bartholin's, not just a tale to tell!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Bartholin cyst. The clinical presentation of a 3 cm, non-tender cystic mass on the labia with a 24-hour onset in a healthy female is highly characteristic of an obstructed Bartholin's gland duct.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBartholin's glands are paired glands located at the posterior-lateral aspect of the vaginal introitus, within the labia majora. Their ducts can become obstructed due to inflammation, infection, or trauma, leading to fluid accumulation and cyst formation. These cysts can rapidly enlarge, presenting as a palpable, often non-tender, cystic mass on the labia, consistent with the 3 cm size and acute onset described in the vignette. If infected, they can progress to a painful abscess, but the initial presentation can be non-tender.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Vaginal adenosis) (Incorrect): Vaginal adenosis involves the presence of glandular tissue in the vagina, typically asymptomatic or causing discharge, and does not present as a discrete, rapidly forming cystic mass on the labia.\nOption C (schic cyst) (Incorrect): Assuming this refers to a sebaceous cyst, these are typically smaller, arise from blocked hair follicles, and usually have a more gradual onset, not presenting as a 3 cm cystic mass on the labia within 24 hours. If it refers to a Skene's gland cyst, these are located periurethrally, not on the labia.\nOption D (hygroma) (Incorrect): A hygroma (lymphatic malformation) is a congenital lymphatic lesion, usually found in the neck or axilla, and is not typically an acute-onset cystic mass on the labia in an adult.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Bartholin's Cyst | Skene's Gland Cyst | Sebaceous Cyst |\n| :-------------- | :------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Location** | Posterior-lateral aspect of vaginal introitus, labia majora | Periurethral, anterior vaginal wall | Labia majora, mons pubis, any hair-bearing skin |\n| **Size** | Can be large (e.g., 3 cm or more) | Usually small (less than 1-2 cm) | Variable, often small (less than 1 cm) |\n| **Onset** | Can be acute (abscess) or gradual (cyst) | Gradual | Gradual |\n| **Symptoms** | Often asymptomatic, pain/dyspareunia if large/infected | Often asymptomatic, dysuria, dyspareunia if large | Asymptomatic, can become inflamed/infected |\n| **Pathogenesis**| Obstruction of Bartholin's duct | Obstruction of Skene's duct | Blockage of sebaceous gland duct |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: A rapidly enlarging cystic mass on the labia is almost always a Bartholin's cyst.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn physical exam, a Bartholin's cyst presents as a soft, fluctuant, non-tender or tender mass in the lower labium majus, often displacing the labium. Imaging is rarely needed for diagnosis but ultrasound would show a well-defined, anechoic or hypoechoic cystic structure.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Committee Opinion No. 701 (2017): Management of Vulvar Lesions. Recommends clinical evaluation for diagnosis and appropriate management based on symptoms and size.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Bartholin cyst | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Vaginal adenosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | schic cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | hygroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A)  Bartholin’s duct cyst: The most common large cyst of vulva – Caused by inflammatory reaction with ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
