  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 If it leaks with a pee, it's from the urethra, you see!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT: The correct diagnosis is urethrovaginal fistula. The key clinical clue is urine passing per vagina specifically *with micturition* following an anterior posterior repair, indicating a direct communication between the urethra and the vagina.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAnterior posterior repair involves dissection of the anterior vaginal wall, which is in close proximity to the urethra. Surgical trauma, ischemia, or infection during this procedure can lead to a breakdown of tissue and formation of a fistula. When the fistula connects the urethra to the vagina, urine will leak into the vagina primarily during the act of voiding, as urethral pressure increases, pushing urine through the defect.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (uretrovaginal fistula): Incorrect. This is a misspelling of urethrovaginal fistula, which is the correct diagnosis.\nOption C (vesicovaginal fistula): Incorrect. A vesicovaginal fistula involves a connection between the bladder and the vagina, typically resulting in continuous urine leakage, not just with micturition, as the bladder constantly fills.\nOption D (sphincter atony): Incorrect. Sphincter atony would cause stress or overflow incontinence, leading to urine leakage from the urethra, but not urine passing *per vagina* through a fistula.\nOption E (Cystitis): Incorrect. Cystitis is a bladder infection causing symptoms like dysuria, frequency, and urgency, but it does not cause urine to pass per vagina.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Fistula Type | Location | Key Symptom | Diagnostic Clue |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Urethrovaginal | Urethra to Vagina | Urine leakage per vagina | Primarily with micturition |\n| Vesicovaginal | Bladder to Vagina | Continuous urine leakage per vagina | Constant leakage, independent of voiding |\n| Ureterovaginal | Ureter to Vagina | Continuous urine leakage per vagina | Normal voiding, but constant leakage from vagina, often unilateral |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Urine per vagina *with micturition* points to urethral involvement.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDiagnosis often involves a combination of physical exam, methylene blue dye test (tampon test), cystoscopy to visualize the urethral opening, and vaginoscopy to identify the vaginal opening. Imaging like a fistulogram or MRI may delineate the tract.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 190, 'Pelvic Organ Prolapse,' 2017, discusses complications of pelvic floor surgery including fistula formation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Urethrovaginal fistula | ✅ Correct |\n| B | uretrovaginal fistula | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | vesicovaginal fistula | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | sphincter atony | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Cystitis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
