  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pop the clot, stop the pain, save the day!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT: The correct management for an acutely thrombosed external hemorrhoid, especially one of this size (3x2 cm), is incision and evacuation of the thrombus under local anesthesia. This provides immediate and definitive pain relief by decompressing the distended perianal skin.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAn acutely thrombosed external hemorrhoid results from thrombosis within the external hemorrhoidal plexus, leading to rapid distension of the overlying perianal skin and severe pain. The pain is due to the somatic innervation of the perianal skin. Incision and evacuation (thrombectomy) directly addresses the pathology by removing the thrombus, thereby relieving pressure and pain. This procedure is most effective when performed within 72 hours of symptom onset, offering superior pain relief and faster resolution compared to conservative management for larger thrombi.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Sitz baths provide symptomatic relief but do not remove the thrombus or offer rapid, definitive pain relief for a large, acutely thrombosed external hemorrhoid.\nOption C (Incorrect): Thrombosed hemorrhoids are not typically infected, so antibiotics are not indicated.\nOption D (Incorrect): Band ligation is reserved for internal hemorrhoids and would be extremely painful and ineffective for an external thrombosed hemorrhoid.\nOption E (Incorrect): Local anesthetic ointments offer temporary, superficial pain relief but do not address the underlying thrombus or provide the rapid, complete relief achieved with incision and evacuation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acutely Thrombosed External Hemorrhoid | Internal Hemorrhoid (Grade I-III) | External Hemorrhoid (Non-thrombosed) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Symptoms** | Severe acute pain, palpable tender lump, blood streaks | Painless bleeding, prolapse, itching | Usually asymptomatic, skin tags |\n| **Location** | Distal to dentate line (somatic innervation) | Proximal to dentate line (visceral innervation) | Distal to dentate line |\n| **Management** | Incision & evacuation (thrombectomy) for acute pain | Band ligation, sclerotherapy, diet/fiber | Conservative, hygiene, excision for skin tags |\n| **Pain** | Severe, acute | Usually painless (unless prolapsed/strangulated) | Mild/none |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute, severe perianal pain + palpable lump = thrombosed external hemorrhoid, manage with thrombectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn examination, a tense, bluish-purple, exquisitely tender mass will be seen at the anal verge, often covered by perianal skin. During incision, a dark, clotted blood mass (thrombus) is evacuated.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Hemorrhoids (2018) recommends excision of acutely thrombosed external hemorrhoids for symptomatic relief, especially within 72 hours of onset.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Sitz bath 5 times/ day. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Application of local anesthetic and incision. | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Application of antibiotic | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Band ligation and wait for it to fall | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Application of local anesthetic ointment | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
