  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't benignly ignore gastric lesions; malignancy often lurks.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, 7%. This percentage reflects the relatively low incidence of truly benign tumors within the stomach compared to the much higher prevalence of malignant gastric neoplasms, primarily adenocarcinoma.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nWhile various benign lesions can occur in the stomach, such as hyperplastic polyps, fundic gland polyps, leiomyomas, and some gastrointestinal stromal tumors (GISTs) with benign behavior, they collectively account for a small fraction of all gastric tumors. Gastric adenocarcinoma remains the predominant gastric malignancy, making up over 90% of all gastric neoplasms. Understanding this prevalence is crucial for risk stratification and diagnostic workup, as the vast majority of gastric lesions encountered will be malignant.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): 20% is significantly higher than the actual prevalence of benign gastric tumors and could lead to underestimating the risk of malignancy.\nOption C (Incorrect): 77% is grossly inaccurate for benign tumors and would imply that benign lesions are far more common than malignant ones, which is contrary to clinical reality.\nOption D (Incorrect): 90% is an extreme overestimation for benign gastric tumors and is closer to the prevalence of malignant gastric adenocarcinoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Benign Gastric Tumors | Malignant Gastric Tumors |\n|---|---|---|\n| Prevalence | ~7% of all gastric neoplasms | ~90-95% of all gastric neoplasms |\n| Common Types | Hyperplastic polyps, Fundic gland polyps, Leiomyomas, Benign GISTs | Adenocarcinoma, Lymphoma, Malignant GISTs, Carcinoid |\n| Clinical Significance | Often asymptomatic, low malignant potential (some polyps) | High morbidity/mortality, aggressive behavior |\n| Management | Surveillance, endoscopic resection (for symptomatic/large lesions) | Surgical resection, chemotherapy, radiation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Benign gastric tumors are rare; malignancy is the rule.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, benign gastric polyps may appear as sessile or pedunculated lesions, often smaller than malignant lesions. Submucosal tumors like leiomyomas or GISTs appear as smooth, elevated lesions covered by normal mucosa, often requiring endoscopic ultrasound for characterization. Intraoperatively, benign lesions are typically well-circumscribed and lack signs of invasion or lymphadenopathy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Gastroenterological Association (AGA) Institute Guidelines on the Management of Gastric Polyps (2012) recommends surveillance or resection based on polyp type and size, acknowledging their benign nature but potential for malignant transformation in some types.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 7% | ✅ Correct |\n| B | 20% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 77% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 90% | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
