  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Aneurysm rupture: the brain's sudden, bloody surprise.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Ruptured cerebral aneurysms are indeed the most frequent cause of non-traumatic subarachnoid hemorrhage, accounting for the vast majority of cases and representing a critical neurosurgical emergency.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCerebral aneurysms, particularly saccular or 'berry' aneurysms, are weakened outpouchings of arterial walls, commonly found at arterial bifurcations within the Circle of Willis. The constant pulsatile pressure within these vessels can lead to progressive thinning and eventual rupture, releasing arterial blood directly into the subarachnoid space. This sudden increase in intracranial pressure and chemical irritation from blood causes the characteristic 'thunderclap' headache and acute neurological deficits, necessitating urgent diagnosis and intervention to prevent rebleeding and vasospasm.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): While other vascular abnormalities like arteriovenous malformations (AVMs) can cause SAH, they are significantly less common than ruptured aneurysms as the primary etiology of non-traumatic SAH.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hypertension is a major risk factor for the development and rupture of cerebral aneurysms, but it is not the direct cause of the hemorrhage itself. The rupture of an aneurysm is the immediate cause, with hypertension being a predisposing factor that exacerbates the risk.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause of SAH | Frequency (Non-traumatic) | Key Feature | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Ruptured Aneurysm | ~85% | Saccular outpouching, often at bifurcations | Endovascular coiling or microsurgical clipping |\n| Perimesencephalic SAH | ~10% | Benign, non-aneurysmal, good prognosis | Conservative, rule out aneurysm |\n| AVM Rupture | ~5% | Tangle of abnormal vessels, direct AV shunting | Embolization, resection, radiosurgery |\n| Other (e.g., vasculitis, coagulopathy) | Rare | Variable | Treat underlying cause |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Thunderclap headache = think ruptured aneurysm until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn non-contrast CT, SAH appears as high-attenuation (white) blood filling the subarachnoid cisterns, sulci, and fissures. Intraoperatively, a ruptured aneurysm appears as a blood-stained, often fragile, outpouching on a cerebral artery, requiring careful dissection and clipping or coiling.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Heart Association/American Stroke Association (AHA/ASA) Guidelines for the Management of Aneurysmal Subarachnoid Hemorrhage (2023). These guidelines emphasize prompt diagnosis, prevention of rebleeding, and management of complications like vasospasm and hydrocephalus.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Rupture aneurysm | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Vessels abnormality | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hypertension | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
  "verified_answer": "A"
