  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Squeeze that vein, if it doesn't compress, it's a clot!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks for the best method to diagnose deep vein thrombosis (DVT) in a patient presenting with leg swelling. Duplex ultrasonography is the current gold standard and preferred initial diagnostic modality due to its non-invasiveness, accuracy, and widespread availability.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuplex ultrasonography combines B-mode imaging to visualize the vein and any thrombus, with Doppler flow studies to assess blood flow and compressibility. The hallmark diagnostic feature of DVT on ultrasound is the inability to fully compress the vein with the transducer, indicating the presence of a thrombus. Doppler helps confirm flow obstruction and can identify non-occlusive thrombi or collateral flow, making it highly sensitive and specific for proximal DVT.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (venography) (Incorrect): Venography is an invasive procedure involving contrast injection and radiation exposure. While historically the gold standard, it has largely been replaced by Duplex US due to its risks, cost, and invasiveness. It is now reserved for cases where ultrasound is inconclusive or technically difficult.\nOption B (Duplex US) (Correct): As detailed above, Duplex US is the current first-line, non-invasive, and highly accurate method for diagnosing DVT.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Diagnostic Method | Principle | Advantages | Disadvantages | Role in DVT Diagnosis |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Duplex US | B-mode imaging + Doppler flow | Non-invasive, no radiation, widely available, high sensitivity/specificity for proximal DVT | Operator-dependent, less sensitive for calf DVT, difficult in obese patients | First-line diagnostic test |\n| Venography | X-ray imaging after contrast injection | Historically gold standard, can visualize entire venous system | Invasive, radiation exposure, contrast nephropathy, allergic reactions, painful | Reserved for inconclusive US or specific clinical scenarios |\n| D-dimer | Blood test for fibrin degradation products | Non-invasive, high negative predictive value | Low specificity (elevated in many conditions), not diagnostic on its own | Rule-out test in low-probability patients |\n| CT Venography | CT imaging after IV contrast | Can visualize pelvic/abdominal veins, good for central DVT | Radiation exposure, contrast nephropathy, higher cost | Useful for suspected central DVT or when US is limited |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Duplex US is the non-invasive, first-line test for DVT.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn Duplex US, a DVT appears as echogenic material within the vein lumen, which prevents complete compression of the vein walls when pressure is applied with the transducer. Color Doppler may show absent or diminished flow distal to the thrombus.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Chest Physicians (ACCP) Guidelines (e.g., 10th edition, 2016 or later updates): Recommend Duplex ultrasonography as the initial diagnostic test for suspected DVT.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | venography | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Duplex US | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
