  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Mallory Weiss: a tear that usually heals itself.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is that Mallory Weiss tears are typically resolved spontaneously. These are superficial mucosal tears at the gastroesophageal junction, often caused by forceful vomiting or retching, and the bleeding is usually self-limited.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMallory Weiss tears result from a sudden increase in intra-abdominal pressure against a closed glottis, leading to a rapid rise in intraluminal esophageal pressure. This causes a linear, non-transmural tear in the mucosa and submucosa, most commonly on the lesser curvature of the stomach or at the gastroesophageal junction. Due to their superficial nature and the rich blood supply, the bleeding often stops spontaneously, and the tears heal without specific intervention in the majority of cases.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While some severe cases may require intervention for persistent bleeding, the vast majority (80-90%) resolve spontaneously without specific medical intervention beyond supportive care. \nOption B (Incorrect): Endoscopy is the diagnostic modality of choice and can be therapeutic for persistent bleeding, but it is not universally 'needed' as many tears resolve before endoscopy is performed or without the need for endoscopic intervention.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Mallory Weiss Tear | Boerhaave Syndrome | Esophageal Varices |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Etiology | Forceful vomiting/retching | Forceful vomiting/retching | Portal hypertension |\n| Pathology | Superficial mucosal tear | Full-thickness esophageal rupture | Dilated submucosal veins |\n| Presentation | Hematemesis, often self-limiting | Severe chest pain, dyspnea, subcutaneous emphysema | Profuse hematemesis, melena |\n| Treatment | Supportive, often spontaneous resolution | Urgent surgical repair, drainage | Endoscopic banding/sclerotherapy, TIPS |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Mallory Weiss tears: self-limiting mucosal tears.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, a Mallory Weiss tear appears as a linear, non-circumferential mucosal laceration, typically located at the gastroesophageal junction, often with adherent clot or active oozing.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Upper Gastrointestinal and Small Bowel Bleeding (2021) - Recommends endoscopy for diagnosis and management of acute upper GI bleeding, noting that Mallory Weiss tears often resolve spontaneously.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It needs medical intervention | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | needs endoscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Resolved spontaneously | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
