  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Jaundice post-chole? ERCP is your best bet!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies ERCP as the most appropriate investigation for progressive jaundice following laparoscopic cholecystectomy. This clinical scenario strongly suggests a bile duct injury or obstruction, for which ERCP offers both diagnostic clarity and therapeutic intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nProgressive jaundice post-cholecystectomy is a critical sign of potential iatrogenic bile duct injury (e.g., stricture, transection, ligation) or retained common bile duct stones. ERCP (Endoscopic Retrograde Cholangiopancreatography) allows for direct visualization of the biliary tree, precise identification of the level and nature of the obstruction or injury, and immediate therapeutic intervention. This includes sphincterotomy, stone extraction, balloon dilation of strictures, or stent placement, making it the gold standard for managing such complications.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (IV cholangiogram) (Incorrect): Intravenous cholangiography is an older, largely obsolete imaging technique. It provides less detailed anatomical information than ERCP or MRCP, requires adequate liver function for contrast excretion (which may be impaired in jaundice), and offers no therapeutic capabilities.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Investigation | Diagnostic Capability | Therapeutic Capability | Invasive | Primary Use in Post-Op Jaundice |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| ERCP | Excellent (direct visualization) | Yes (stone extraction, stenting, dilation) | Yes | Diagnostic and therapeutic for obstruction/injury |\n| MRCP | Excellent (non-invasive imaging) | No | No | Initial non-invasive diagnostic for obstruction/injury |\n| IV Cholangiogram | Limited (older technique) | No | Yes (contrast injection) | Largely obsolete; replaced by MRCP/ERCP |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Post-cholecystectomy jaundice = ERCP for diagnosis and treatment.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ERCP, one might observe dilated intrahepatic ducts, a stricture or transection of the common bile duct, retained common bile duct stones, or contrast extravasation indicating a bile leak.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASGE Standards of Practice Committee, 2019: The role of endoscopy in the management of choledocholithiasis. This guideline supports ERCP for diagnosis and management of biliary obstruction.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | ERCP | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | IV cholangiogram | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
