  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't be yellow about jaundice in cholangitis!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT: Option C is the correct answer because jaundice is a cardinal symptom of acute cholangitis, not an uncommon one. The question asks for the statement that is NOT true, and 'Jaundice is uncommon' is definitively false.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute cholangitis is an ascending bacterial infection of the bile ducts, typically occurring in the setting of biliary obstruction. Jaundice, along with fever and right upper quadrant pain, forms Charcot's triad, which is present in 50-75% of patients. In more severe cases, altered mental status and hypotension are added to form Reynolds' pentad. The presence of jaundice is a direct consequence of biliary obstruction and inflammation, making it a common and expected finding.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): E. coli is indeed the most common causative organism in acute cholangitis, often ascending from the duodenum. Other common organisms include Klebsiella, Enterococcus, and Bacteroides.\nOption B (Incorrect): Septic shock is a severe and life-threatening complication of acute cholangitis, particularly in cases of severe obstruction and delayed decompression. It is a major cause of morbidity and mortality.\nOption D (Incorrect): ERCP with sphincterotomy and stone extraction or stent placement is a highly effective and often preferred method for biliary decompression in acute cholangitis, especially in moderate to severe cases. It provides both diagnostic and therapeutic capabilities.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Charcot's Triad | Reynolds' Pentad |\n| :------ | :-------------- | :--------------- |\n| Components | Fever, RUQ Pain, Jaundice | Fever, RUQ Pain, Jaundice, Altered Mental Status, Hypotension |\n| Severity | Indicates acute cholangitis | Indicates severe/suppurative cholangitis |\n| Prognosis | Requires urgent treatment | Requires emergent decompression and ICU care |\n| Frequency | Present in 50-75% of cases | Present in ~10-15% of cases |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Jaundice is a hallmark, not a rarity, in acute cholangitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (ultrasound, CT, MRCP) typically reveals dilated intrahepatic and/or extrahepatic bile ducts, often with evidence of choledocholithiasis or other obstructing lesions. Intraoperatively, the common bile duct may appear distended and inflamed, and purulent bile may be expressed upon choledochotomy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 for the management of acute cholangitis and cholecystitis. They recommend early diagnosis, severity assessment, initial medical treatment (antibiotics, supportive care), and timely biliary drainage (ERCP, percutaneous, or surgical) based on severity.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | E-coli is most common organism | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Septic shock is most likely complication | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Jaundice is uncommon | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | ERCP and papillotomy is best treatment | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
