  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 One cord paralyzed? Voice change. Both cords paralyzed? Airway emergency!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks for an option that is NOT an indication for tracheotomy. A unilateral left recurrent laryngeal nerve (RLN) cut typically causes ipsilateral vocal cord paralysis, leading to hoarseness and potential aspiration, but generally does not cause acute airway obstruction requiring tracheotomy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe recurrent laryngeal nerve innervates all intrinsic laryngeal muscles except the cricothyroid. A unilateral injury results in paralysis of one vocal cord, which usually rests in a paramedian or cadaveric position, allowing sufficient glottic opening for respiration. While voice changes and aspiration risk are significant, the airway typically remains patent. In contrast, bilateral RLN paralysis often leads to severe airway obstruction due to adduction of both vocal cords, necessitating emergent airway management, frequently a tracheotomy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): A foreign body in the larynx causing acute airway obstruction is a critical indication for securing the airway, often requiring tracheotomy if intubation is not feasible or fails.\nOption C (Incorrect): Carcinoma of the larynx can cause significant airway obstruction due to tumor bulk, edema, or post-treatment complications, making tracheotomy a common necessity for airway management.\nOption D (Incorrect): Procedures involving radiation exposure, particularly radiation therapy for head and neck cancers, can lead to severe laryngeal edema, mucositis, and necrosis, causing airway compromise that frequently requires tracheotomy.\nOption E (Incorrect): Since 'Left recurrent nerve cut' (assuming unilateral) is not typically an indication, this option is incorrect.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Indication for Tracheotomy | Clinical Scenario |\n|---------------------------|-------------------|\n| Prolonged mechanical ventilation | >7-10 days, to reduce laryngeal injury |\n| Upper airway obstruction   | Tumor, trauma, infection, foreign body |\n| Inability to intubate     | Failed intubation, severe facial trauma |\n| Airway protection         | Severe aspiration risk, impaired cough |\n| Bilateral vocal cord paralysis | Adduction of vocal cords causing obstruction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unilateral RLN injury causes voice change; bilateral RLN injury causes airway obstruction.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring direct laryngoscopy for a unilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve injury, one would observe the affected vocal cord remaining immobile in a paramedian or cadaveric position during phonation and respiration, while the contralateral cord moves normally. For other indications like laryngeal cancer, a mass or significant edema would be visible.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology–Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Tracheostomy (2013) recommends considering tracheostomy for prolonged airway management or severe upper airway obstruction.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | foreign body in larynx | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Left recurrent nerve cut | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | CA larynx | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | In some procedure which involve in radiation exposure | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | None of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
