  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Stomas cause problems, but water malabsorption isn't one of them!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Malabsorption of water. While colostomies can alter fluid balance, true \"malabsorption of water\" is not a primary or typical complication in the same manner as mechanical issues or skin irritation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nColostomies are surgical procedures that create an opening (stoma) from the colon to the body surface, diverting fecal matter. The large intestine's primary role is water and electrolyte absorption. While diverting the colon can lead to increased fluid output, especially with more proximal stomas, the term \"malabsorption\" typically refers to impaired absorption of nutrients in the small intestine. The other options represent common and direct mechanical or dermatological complications directly related to the stoma's presence and function.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Prolapse is a common mechanical complication where the bowel protrudes through the stoma, often requiring surgical revision.\nOption C (Incorrect): Retraction occurs when the stoma pulls back below the skin level, leading to leakage, skin irritation, and difficulty with appliance adherence.\nOption D (Incorrect): Obstruction can result from stricture at the stoma site, fecal impaction, or internal herniation, preventing the passage of stool.\nOption E (Incorrect): Excoriation of skin, or peristomal dermatitis, is a very common complication caused by irritation from effluent leaking onto the surrounding skin.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication Type | Description | Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Mechanical** | Prolapse, Retraction, Obstruction | Surgical revision, stoma care, dietary modification |\n| **Dermatological** | Excoriation, Dermatitis | Skin barriers, proper appliance fit, topical treatments |\n| **Fluid/Electrolyte** | Dehydration, Electrolyte imbalance (more common with ileostomy) | Fluid replacement, electrolyte monitoring, dietary advice |\n| **Infectious** | Stoma infection, Abscess | Antibiotics, drainage |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Colostomy complications are usually mechanical, dermatological, or infectious, not true malabsorption.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a well-constructed colostomy should have a healthy, pink, everted stoma without tension. Imaging like a contrast enema (colostogram) can identify strictures or obstructions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for Ostomy Surgery (2020) recommends proper stoma site selection and surgical technique to minimize complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Malabsorption of water | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Prolapse. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Retraction. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Obstruction. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Excoriation of skin. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
