  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Stillness signals peritonitis's severe sting.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT, Option B is correct. Patients with peritonitis typically lie still to minimize movement, as any motion exacerbates the severe pain caused by peritoneal inflammation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe peritoneum is richly innervated, and its inflammation (peritonitis) leads to intense somatic pain. Movement, coughing, or even deep breathing stretches the inflamed peritoneum, causing excruciating pain. Consequently, patients adopt a characteristic posture of lying still, often with knees drawn up, to reduce abdominal wall tension and avoid any motion that might aggravate their discomfort. This stillness is a protective mechanism against the severe pain.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Patients with peritonitis avoid movement, including rolling over, because it intensifies their pain by irritating the inflamed peritoneum. They do not writhe or roll with agony like in renal colic. \nOption C (Incorrect): Peritonitis is an inflammatory process often associated with systemic inflammatory response, pain, and potential hypovolemia/sepsis, all of which typically cause tachycardia (increased pulse rate), not bradycardia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Sign | Peritonitis | Renal Colic | Bowel Obstruction |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Patient Movement** | Lies still, avoids movement | Restless, writhing in pain | Restless, colicky pain |\n| **Abdominal Tenderness** | Diffuse, severe, guarding, rigidity | Flank/loin pain, often radiating | Variable, distension, tenderness |\n| **Pulse Rate** | Tachycardia | Tachycardia (due to pain) | Tachycardia (dehydration, sepsis) |\n| **Pain Character** | Constant, severe, sharp | Intermittent, colicky, excruciating | Intermittent, colicky, cramping |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Peritonitis patients lie still; movement is agony.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT scan), findings may include free intra-abdominal air (indicating perforation), free fluid, bowel wall thickening, or inflammatory stranding. Intraoperatively, one would observe diffuse erythema, edema, fibrin exudates on the peritoneal surfaces, and often purulent or feculent fluid within the abdominal cavity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Intra-abdominal Infections (2017) recommend prompt diagnosis and source control for peritonitis, emphasizing clinical signs like guarding and rigidity.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The patient rolls over with agony (pain) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The patient lies still. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pulse rate is decreased. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
