  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Free air on X-ray means go to the OR, fast!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient presents with classic signs and symptoms of acute peritonitis, characterized by severe abdominal pain, fetal position, and inability to straighten. In such a critical scenario, the immediate priority is to identify life-threatening causes, particularly a perforated viscus. A plain X-ray is the most appropriate initial imaging study to rule out this emergent condition.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPeritonitis, especially with severe pain and guarding, demands rapid assessment for surgical emergencies. A plain abdominal X-ray, particularly an upright chest X-ray, is highly sensitive for detecting free intraperitoneal air, a hallmark of gastrointestinal perforation. This finding mandates immediate surgical consultation and intervention, making it a critical first step in investigation to guide urgent management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (US) (Incorrect): While useful for some abdominal pathologies (e.g., appendicitis, cholecystitis, free fluid), ultrasound is operator-dependent and less sensitive for detecting free air compared to X-ray or CT. It is not the primary initial step to rule out a perforated viscus.\nOption B (CBC with differential) (Incorrect): This is a laboratory test that provides supportive information (e.g., leukocytosis indicating infection/inflammation) but does not localize the source of peritonitis or rule out surgical emergencies like perforation. It is not an initial investigative step to determine the *cause*.\nOption D (Paracentesis) (Incorrect): This is an invasive procedure to obtain peritoneal fluid. It is typically reserved for diagnosing ascites or spontaneous bacterial peritonitis, or in cases of trauma with suspected hemoperitoneum, not as the primary initial investigation for acute peritonitis in a young male without clear ascites.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Investigation | Primary Use in Acute Abdomen | Key Finding for Peritonitis | Limitations |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Plain X-ray (Upright Chest/Abdomen) | Rule out perforation, obstruction | Free air under diaphragm | Limited soft tissue detail, not sensitive for all causes |\n| Ultrasound (US) | Appendicitis, cholecystitis, gynecologic, free fluid | Inflamed appendix, gallstones, free fluid | Operator-dependent, poor for free air, bowel gas interference |\n| CBC with differential | Assess inflammation/infection | Leukocytosis, left shift | Non-specific, doesn't localize pathology |\n| CT Scan (with contrast) | Comprehensive imaging for most causes | Perforation, inflammation, abscess, obstruction | Radiation exposure, contrast risks, not always \"first\" due to availability/time |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Peritonitis + severe pain = rule out perforation with X-ray first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn an upright chest X-ray, look for a crescent-shaped lucency (air) under the diaphragm, often more prominent on the right side. This finding confirms pneumoperitoneum, indicating a perforated viscus.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) Appropriateness Criteria for Acute Abdominal Pain (2022). Recommends plain radiographs (X-ray) as an initial step, especially when perforation or obstruction is suspected, followed by CT if the diagnosis remains unclear or for further characterization.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | US | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | CBC with differential | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | X RAY | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Paracentesis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
