  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Small cuts, big gains: Lap chole, less pain, faster drain.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that \"Commonest complication is wound infection\" is the false statement regarding laparoscopic cholecystectomy. Laparoscopic surgery significantly reduces incision size, thereby lowering the incidence of wound-related complications compared to open surgery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLaparoscopic cholecystectomy revolutionized gallbladder surgery by minimizing surgical trauma. The small incisions lead to less pain, faster recovery, and a significantly reduced risk of wound infection, which was a more common issue with large open incisions. This approach leverages advanced optics and instrumentation to achieve surgical goals with minimal disruption to surrounding tissues, making it the gold standard for symptomatic cholelithiasis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Correct - EXCEPT statement): \"Commonest complication is wound infection.\" (Incorrect statement): Wound infection is not the commonest complication of laparoscopic cholecystectomy; bile duct injury, bleeding, or other minor issues are more prevalent, but overall complication rates are low.\nOption B (Incorrect): \"Patient re-admission is frequent.\" (Correct statement): While readmission can occur for various reasons, it is not considered \"frequent\" after an uncomplicated laparoscopic cholecystectomy, which is generally a safe procedure.\nOption C (Incorrect): \"Pt can be discharged after 1-2 days.\" (Correct statement): This is true; laparoscopic cholecystectomy is often performed as an outpatient procedure or with a short overnight stay, allowing discharge within 1-2 days.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Laparoscopic Cholecystectomy | Open Cholecystectomy |\n| :-------------------- | :--------------------------- | :------------------- |\n| Incision Size | Small (multiple ports) | Large (subcostal/midline) |\n| Wound Infection Risk | Low | Higher |\n| Post-op Pain | Less | More |\n| Hospital Stay | 0-1 day | 3-5 days |\n| Recovery Time | Faster | Slower |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Laparoscopic cholecystectomy minimizes wound complications and speeds recovery compared to open surgery.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the critical view of safety (CVS) must be achieved to prevent bile duct injury, often confirmed with intraoperative cholangiography.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES (Society of American Gastrointestinal and Endoscopic Surgeons) Guidelines for Laparoscopic Cholecystectomy (2010, updated periodically) recommend its use as the standard approach for symptomatic cholelithiasis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Commonest complication is wound infection. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Patient re-admission is frequent | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pt can be discharged after 1-2 days. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
