  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the submandibular gland aches, US is the first step to take!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. Ultrasound (US) is the correct first investigation for submandibular swelling with pain during eating because it is a non-invasive, readily available, and effective initial imaging modality for suspected sialolithiasis or sialadenitis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUltrasound allows for dynamic assessment of the salivary glands and ducts. It can accurately identify sialoliths (stones), even radiolucent ones, by visualizing hyperechoic foci with posterior acoustic shadowing. Furthermore, US can detect ductal dilation, glandular inflammation, and abscess formation, providing crucial information for guiding further management without exposing the patient to radiation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): X-ray is limited as it only detects radiopaque stones (80-90% of submandibular stones) and provides poor soft tissue detail, missing radiolucent stones or inflammatory changes.\nOption B (Incorrect): MRI offers excellent soft tissue contrast but is not typically the first-line investigation due to higher cost, longer scan times, and limited availability compared to US. It is reserved for complex cases or when US/CT are inconclusive.\nOption C (Incorrect): CT is highly effective for detecting stones and providing detailed anatomy but involves radiation exposure. While a good second-line option, US is preferred as the initial, non-invasive investigation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Imaging Modality | Advantages | Disadvantages | Role in Sialolithiasis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Ultrasound (US) | Non-invasive, no radiation, readily available, dynamic, detects stones (radio-opaque & lucent), inflammation | Operator dependent, limited by deep structures/bone | First-line investigation |\n| Plain X-ray | Inexpensive, quick | Radiation, only detects radiopaque stones, poor soft tissue | Limited utility, can miss stones |\n| CT Scan | Excellent detail, detects all stones, good for complex anatomy | Radiation exposure, higher cost than US | Second-line, pre-operative planning |\n| MRI/MR Sialography | No radiation, excellent soft tissue, good for ductal anatomy | High cost, long scan time, limited stone detection compared to CT | Complex cases, ductal pathology, tumors |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For salivary gland pain with eating, think US first for stones and inflammation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a sialolith appears as a hyperechoic (bright) focus within the salivary duct or gland parenchyma, often with posterior acoustic shadowing. The gland itself may appear enlarged and hypoechoic due to inflammation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nMost international guidelines for salivary gland pathology, including those from major ENT and Radiology societies, recommend ultrasound as the initial imaging modality for suspected sialolithiasis or sialadenitis due to its safety and efficacy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | X-ray | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | MRI | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | CT | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | US | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
