  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When food makes your submandibular gland ache, think stone, not steak!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Salivary calculi. This diagnosis perfectly aligns with the classic presentation of acute, intermittent submandibular gland pain and swelling exacerbated by eating, which stimulates salivary flow against an obstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSalivary calculi, or sialolithiasis, typically form in Wharton's duct of the submandibular gland due to its long, tortuous path and gravity. During mastication, increased parasympathetic stimulation leads to a surge in salivary production. If a calculus obstructs the duct, saliva backs up, causing acute distension of the gland, leading to pain and swelling. The firm consistency on examination is consistent with an inflamed, obstructed gland.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Mumps) (Incorrect): Mumps typically affects the parotid gland, is viral, often bilateral, and presents with systemic symptoms like fever, not usually localized submandibular pain exacerbated by eating.\nOption B (Sjogren’s syndrome) (Incorrect): Sjogren's is an autoimmune disease causing chronic dry mouth and eyes, and diffuse, often bilateral, non-tender salivary gland enlargement, not acute pain with eating.\nOption C (Hodgkin’s lymphoma) (Incorrect): Lymphoma in the submandibular region would typically present as a painless, firm mass, often with generalized lymphadenopathy and and B symptoms, not acute pain and swelling related to eating.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Salivary Calculi (Sialolithiasis) | Mumps | Sjogren's Syndrome | Hodgkin's Lymphoma |\n| :------------------ | :-------------------------------- | :---------------------------------- | :-------------------------------------- | :-------------------------------------- |\n| **Key Symptom** | Pain/swelling with eating | Parotid swelling, fever | Dry mouth/eyes, chronic enlargement | Painless mass, B symptoms |\n| **Gland Affected** | Submandibular (80-90%), Parotid | Parotid (most common) | Parotid, Submandibular (diffuse) | Lymph nodes, sometimes salivary glands |\n| **Nature of Swelling** | Intermittent, acute, firm | Acute, tender, diffuse | Chronic, diffuse, non-tender | Firm, non-tender mass |\n| **Etiology** | Obstruction by calculus | Viral (paramyxovirus) | Autoimmune | Malignancy of lymphocytes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute submandibular pain with eating = sialolithiasis until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPlain film (occlusal view) can detect radiopaque calculi (80-90% of submandibular stones). Ultrasound can identify stones and ductal dilation. CT scan is highly sensitive for all calculi and can assess gland parenchyma. Sialography can delineate ductal anatomy and obstructions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology–Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Sialolithiasis (2019). Recommends initial imaging with ultrasound or CT for suspected sialolithiasis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Mumps | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Sjogren’s syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hodgkin’s lymphoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Salivary calculi | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
