  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 UC: Continuous, superficial, crypts in the colon.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is Ulcerative Colitis. This diagnosis is strongly supported by the continuous colonic involvement from the rectum to the mid-transverse colon and the biopsy showing crypt abscesses without epithelial ulceration, which are classic features of UC.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUlcerative colitis is characterized by continuous inflammation that always involves the rectum and extends proximally, affecting only the colon. The inflammation is typically superficial, limited to the mucosa and submucosa. Histologically, crypt abscesses are a hallmark, representing collections of neutrophils within the crypt lumen. The absence of transmural inflammation, skip lesions, or granulomas helps distinguish it from Crohn's disease.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Crohn's disease) (Incorrect): Crohn's disease typically presents with skip lesions, transmural inflammation, and often involves the small bowel, which contradicts the continuous colonic involvement described. Granulomas are also characteristic of Crohn's, not crypt abscesses without ulceration.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Ulcerative Colitis | Crohn's Disease |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Location** | Colon only, always involves rectum | Any part of GI tract, often terminal ileum & colon |\n| **Pattern** | Continuous, circumferential | Skip lesions, segmental |\n| **Depth** | Mucosa & submucosa | Transmural |\n| **Histology** | Crypt abscesses, no granulomas | Granulomas, transmural inflammation |\n| **Perianal Disease** | Rare | Common (fistulas, abscesses) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Continuous rectal involvement with crypt abscesses points to Ulcerative Colitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nColonoscopy would reveal continuous erythema, friability, loss of vascular pattern, and possibly pseudopolyps extending from the rectum proximally, without intervening areas of normal mucosa or skip lesions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guidelines: Ulcerative Colitis in Adults (2019) recommends colonoscopy with biopsy for diagnosis and assessment of disease extent.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Crohn's disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Ulcerative colitis | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
