  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Water content isn't fixed; it's a fluid concept!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, \"Difference depend on age and sex.\" This option accurately reflects the physiological reality that total body water (TBW) is not a fixed percentage but varies significantly based on individual characteristics.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTotal body water constitutes a major portion of body weight, but its exact percentage is highly dynamic. Lean body mass contains a higher percentage of water than adipose tissue. Since body composition changes with age (e.g., decreased lean mass in elderly) and sex (e.g., higher average body fat in females), the proportion of water in the body also changes. Infants have the highest percentage of body water, while the elderly typically have the lowest.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 40 % is generally too low for an average adult and does not account for the wide variability seen across different populations. While some individuals (e.g., very obese or elderly) might approach this percentage, it is not a universally representative figure for total body water.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Demographic | Approximate Total Body Water (% of body weight) |\n|---|---|\n| Infants | 75-80% |\n| Adult Males | 60% |\n| Adult Females | 50-55% |\n| Elderly | 45-50% |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Total body water varies significantly by age, sex, and body composition.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFluid balance is critical in surgical patients, requiring careful monitoring of intake/output and electrolyte levels, especially in patients with altered body water distribution due to age, comorbidities, or significant fluid shifts.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo specific surgical guideline directly addresses the percentage of water in the body. However, principles of fluid management are outlined in critical care and surgical guidelines, such as the 'Enhanced Recovery After Surgery (ERAS) Society Guidelines' (various years, e.g., 2018 for colorectal surgery) which emphasize appropriate perioperative fluid administration.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 40 % | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Difference depend on age and sex | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
