  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When gallstones cause pain, the gallbladder must go!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, \"Remove gallbladder by surgery.\" This patient presents with symptomatic cholelithiasis, characterized by recurrent abdominal pain associated with gallstones. Surgical removal of the gallbladder (cholecystectomy) is the definitive treatment for symptomatic gallstones.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBiliary colic, the 'on and off episodes of abdominal pain,' is caused by transient obstruction of the cystic duct by a gallstone, leading to gallbladder distension and visceral pain. While the obstruction may resolve spontaneously, the underlying gallstones remain, and symptoms are highly likely to recur. Furthermore, symptomatic gallstones carry a significant risk of progressing to more severe complications such as acute cholecystitis, choledocholithiasis, gallstone pancreatitis, or cholangitis. Cholecystectomy eliminates the source of these symptoms and prevents future complications, offering a cure.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Give pain killers medication. Painkillers only provide symptomatic relief and do not address the underlying pathology of gallstones. This approach leaves the patient vulnerable to recurrent pain and the potential for serious complications, making it an inappropriate definitive management strategy for symptomatic cholelithiasis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Symptomatic Cholelithiasis | Asymptomatic Cholelithiasis |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------------------------- | :-------------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Symptoms** | Recurrent biliary colic (RUQ pain, nausea, vomiting) | None, incidental finding |\n| **Diagnosis** | Ultrasound showing gallstones + symptoms | Ultrasound showing gallstones, no symptoms |\n| **Management** | Laparoscopic Cholecystectomy (definitive) | Observation (unless specific risk factors) |\n| **Risk of Complications** | High (cholecystitis, choledocholithiasis, pancreatitis) | Low (approx. 1-2% per year) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Symptomatic gallstones demand surgical removal, not just pain management.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, you would see multiple echogenic foci with posterior acoustic shadowing within the gallbladder lumen, confirming gallstones. The common bile duct would likely be of normal caliber, indicating no current ductal obstruction. Intraoperatively, the gallbladder may appear normal or show signs of chronic inflammation such as thickening of the wall or adhesions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES Clinical Practice Guidelines on the Surgical Management of Gallstones (2019) recommends laparoscopic cholecystectomy as the treatment of choice for symptomatic cholelithiasis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Give pain killers medication | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Remove gallbladder by surgery | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
