  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 High INR, urgent surgery? FFP is your friend!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Fresh frozen plasma (FFP). A patient presenting with a perforated peptic ulcer requires emergent surgical intervention, and an INR of 5 indicates severe coagulopathy, necessitating rapid reversal to prevent life-threatening hemorrhage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFFP contains all plasma coagulation factors, including labile factors V and VIII, and fibrinogen. Administering FFP rapidly replenishes these deficient factors, thereby correcting the coagulopathy and lowering the INR. This immediate restoration of clotting factor levels is crucial for patients requiring urgent surgery, as it significantly reduces the risk of excessive bleeding during the procedure.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Protamine sulfate) (Incorrect): Protamine sulfate is used to reverse the anticoagulant effects of heparin, not warfarin or other causes of elevated INR.\nOption B (Frozen blood) (Incorrect): 'Frozen blood' is not a standard blood product used for coagulopathy reversal. Blood is typically separated into components like packed red blood cells, plasma, and platelets.\nOption D (fresh frozen blood) (Incorrect): Similar to 'frozen blood,' 'fresh frozen blood' is not a recognized blood product for correcting coagulopathy. Fresh frozen plasma (FFP) is the correct term for the plasma component used for this purpose.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Product | Indication | Mechanism | Onset |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Fresh Frozen Plasma (FFP) | Emergent INR reversal, multiple factor deficiencies | Replaces all plasma coagulation factors | Rapid (minutes) |\n| Protamine Sulfate | Heparin reversal | Binds and neutralizes heparin | Immediate |\n| Vitamin K | Warfarin reversal (non-emergent) | Promotes hepatic synthesis of clotting factors II, VII, IX, X | Hours to days |\n| Prothrombin Complex Concentrate (PCC) | Emergent warfarin reversal | Provides concentrated factors II, VII, IX, X | Rapid (minutes) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Emergent INR reversal for surgery? Think FFP or PCC.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn an upright chest X-ray or CT scan, a perforated peptic ulcer typically presents with free air under the diaphragm (pneumoperitoneum). Intraoperatively, one would observe a gastric or duodenal perforation with spillage of gastric contents or bile into the peritoneal cavity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Anesthesiologists (ASA) Practice Guidelines for Perioperative Blood Management (2015) recommend FFP or PCC for rapid reversal of warfarin-induced coagulopathy in patients requiring urgent surgery.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Protamine sulfate | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Frozen blood | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Fresh frozen plasma | ✅ Correct |\n| D | fresh frozen blood | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
