  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When calcium climbs in the hospital, think cancer first.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Cancer. Malignancy is the most common cause of hypercalcaemia in hospitalized patients, accounting for approximately 80% of cases in this setting. This is a critical distinction from outpatient hypercalcaemia, where primary hyperparathyroidism is most prevalent.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMalignancy-associated hypercalcaemia (MAH) arises through several mechanisms. The most common is humoral hypercalcaemia of malignancy (HHM), where tumors (e.g., squamous cell carcinoma, renal cell carcinoma) secrete parathyroid hormone-related protein (PTHrP). PTHrP mimics PTH, leading to increased bone resorption and renal calcium reabsorption. Other mechanisms include direct osteolytic metastases (e.g., multiple myeloma, breast cancer) causing bone destruction and calcium release, and rarely, ectopic production of calcitriol (1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D) by lymphomas, which increases intestinal calcium absorption.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Dietary, such as milk-alkali syndrome. While a recognized cause, it is far less common than malignancy in hospitalized patients.\nOption B (Incorrect): Drug related, such as the use of thiazide diuretics. Thiazide diuretics can reduce renal calcium excretion and exacerbate existing hypercalcaemia, but they are rarely the primary cause of significant hypercalcaemia requiring hospitalization.\nOption C (Incorrect): Granulomatous disease. Conditions like sarcoidosis can cause hypercalcaemia due to increased extrarenal production of calcitriol, but this is less frequent than malignancy.\nOption E (Incorrect): Dehydration. Dehydration can worsen hypercalcaemia by increasing hemoconcentration and reducing renal calcium excretion, but it is typically a contributing factor or a consequence, not the primary underlying etiology.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause of Hypercalcaemia | Most Common Outpatient | Most Common Inpatient | Primary Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Primary Hyperparathyroidism | Yes | No | Excess PTH secretion |\n| Malignancy | No | Yes | PTHrP, osteolysis, calcitriol |\n| Other Causes (Drugs, Granulomas, etc.) | Less common | Less common | Variable (e.g., altered vitamin D metabolism, increased absorption) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Inpatient hypercalcaemia? Think cancer. Outpatient? Think parathyroid.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging studies (e.g., CT, PET scans, bone scans) would often reveal the underlying malignancy, such as a primary tumor, metastatic bone lesions, or lymphadenopathy. Intraoperatively, one might encounter the tumor itself or evidence of metastatic disease in relevant surgical fields.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Hypercalcemia of Malignancy (2016) emphasize prompt diagnosis of the underlying malignancy and appropriate treatment to manage calcium levels.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Dietary, such as milk-alkali syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Drug related, such as the use of thiazide diuretics. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Granulomatous disease. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Dehydration. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
