  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Meckel's in adults: It's all about the block!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Intestinal obstruction. In adults, Meckel's diverticulum most frequently presents with complications related to mechanical obstruction of the small bowel, making it the most common presentation in this age group.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMeckel's diverticulum is a true diverticulum, a remnant of the omphalomesenteric duct. In adults, its fibrous band or the diverticulum itself can act as a lead point for intussusception, a fulcrum for volvulus of the small bowel, or become incarcerated in a hernia (Littre's hernia). Adhesions from prior inflammation can also cause obstruction. These mechanical issues collectively make intestinal obstruction the predominant complication in adults, often requiring emergent surgical intervention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Bleeding): Incorrect. While bleeding is the most common complication overall, it is predominantly seen in children due to ectopic gastric mucosa causing ulceration. It is less common in adults.\nOption B (Perforation): Incorrect. Perforation can occur, but it is usually secondary to diverticulitis, ischemia from obstruction, or ulceration, rather than being the primary most common complication itself.\nOption D (Ulceration): Incorrect. Ulceration, typically caused by ectopic gastric mucosa, is the underlying pathology leading to bleeding, but bleeding is the complication, and obstruction is more common in adults.\nOption E (Carcinoma): Incorrect. Carcinoma (e.g., adenocarcinoma, carcinoid) arising in a Meckel's diverticulum is exceedingly rare, making it far from the most common complication.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Adults | Children |\n|---|---|---|\n| Intestinal Obstruction | Most Common | Less Common (can occur) |\n| Bleeding | Less Common | Most Common |\n| Diverticulitis | Common | Less Common |\n| Perforation | Secondary to other issues | Secondary to other issues |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Adult Meckel's: Think obstruction. Child Meckel's: Think bleeding.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT scan), one might see dilated small bowel loops proximal to an obstruction, with the Meckel's diverticulum potentially visible as a blind-ending pouch. Intraoperatively, the diverticulum may be found acting as a lead point for intussusception, forming a loop for a volvulus, or incarcerated within a hernia sac. The presence of a fibrous band connecting the diverticulum to the umbilicus or mesentery is a key finding.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThere are no specific society guidelines solely dedicated to Meckel's diverticulum complications. Management typically follows general surgical principles for small bowel obstruction and acute abdomen, as outlined in standard surgical textbooks like Sabiston Textbook of Surgery (21st ed., 2021) or Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (11th ed., 2019).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Bleeding | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Perforation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Intestinal obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Ulceration | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Carcinoma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
