  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Sunburn is a first-degree burn, don't forget your SPF!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 1st degree burn. The patient's symptoms of red, reblanchable, and painful skin after UV exposure are pathognomonic for a superficial epidermal burn, which is classified as a first-degree burn.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFirst-degree burns involve only the epidermis, the outermost layer of the skin. The redness (erythema) is due to vasodilation in the underlying dermis, which is why it is reblanchable. The pain results from irritation of nerve endings within the epidermis and superficial dermis. Since the dermis is not significantly damaged, there is no blistering, and healing typically occurs without scarring as the epidermal cells regenerate.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (2nd degree burn): Incorrect: Second-degree burns involve the epidermis and a portion of the dermis, typically presenting with blistering in addition to redness and pain. The description does not mention blistering.\nOption C (3rd degree burn): Incorrect: Third-degree burns extend through all layers of the skin, often appearing white, leathery, or charred, and are typically insensate due to nerve destruction. The described symptoms do not match this severity.\nOption D (skin prodromal): Incorrect: 'Skin prodromal' is not a recognized medical term for a skin condition or burn classification. A prodrome refers to an early symptom indicating the onset of a disease.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Burn Degree | Layers Involved | Appearance | Sensation | Healing |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1st Degree | Epidermis | Red, dry, reblanchable | Painful | 3-6 days, no scar |\n| 2nd Degree (Superficial Partial) | Epidermis + superficial dermis | Red, moist, blistered, reblanchable | Very painful | 7-21 days, minimal scar |\n| 2nd Degree (Deep Partial) | Epidermis + deep dermis | Red/white, dry, less blanching, less painful | Painful, pressure sensation | 3-9 weeks, significant scar |\n| 3rd Degree | All skin layers | White, leathery, charred, non-blanching | Insensate | Requires grafting, significant scar |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Red, reblanchable, painful skin = 1st degree burn.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNo specific imaging is indicated for 1st-degree burns. Diagnosis is clinical.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Burn Association (ABA) Practice Guidelines for Burn Care (2018): Recommends clinical assessment for burn depth classification and outlines management strategies based on burn severity.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 1st degree burn | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 2nd degree burn | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 3rd degree burn | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | skin prodromal | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
