  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lobular's lack of E-cadherin makes it a bilateral bad actor.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nLobar carcinoma, interpreted as Invasive Lobular Carcinoma (ILC), is the correct answer because it is the type of invasive breast cancer most frequently associated with bilateral disease. Its unique cellular characteristics contribute to a higher incidence of multifocal, multicentric, and contralateral breast involvement.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInvasive Lobular Carcinoma (ILC) is characterized by a loss of E-cadherin expression, which leads to a discohesive growth pattern. This allows tumor cells to infiltrate tissues in a single-file fashion, making it prone to diffuse spread within the breast and a higher likelihood of developing in the contralateral breast, often synchronously or metachronously.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Paget’s disease) (Incorrect): Paget's disease of the breast is a rare form of breast cancer involving the nipple and areola, and it is almost exclusively unilateral.\nOption C (Invasive ductal carcinoma) (Incorrect): While invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) can occur bilaterally, it does so less frequently than invasive lobular carcinoma. IDC typically forms a discrete mass.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Invasive Ductal Carcinoma (IDC) | Invasive Lobular Carcinoma (ILC) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Incidence | ~75-80% of all invasive breast cancers | ~10-15% of all invasive breast cancers |\n| E-cadherin | Present | Absent |\n| Growth Pattern | Cohesive cells, forms ducts/masses | Discohesive cells, single-file infiltration |\n| Bilaterality | Less common (5-10%) | More common (15-30%) |\n| Palpation | Often discrete mass | Often subtle, diffuse thickening |\n| Imaging | Well-defined mass, calcifications | Often subtle, architectural distortion, less distinct mass |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think lobular for bilateral breast cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammography, ILC can be subtle, presenting as architectural distortion or asymmetry rather than a distinct mass. Ultrasound may show ill-defined hypoechoic areas, and MRI is often superior for detecting the extent of disease and bilaterality due to its diffuse infiltrative nature.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Clinical Practice Guidelines in Oncology (NCCN Guidelines®) for Breast Cancer (e.g., Version 3.2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for screening, diagnosis, and management, including considerations for bilaterality in ILC.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lobar carcinoma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Paget’s disease. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Invasive ductal carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
