  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cool water is your burn's best friend, not ice or butter!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The correct answer is A. Immediate cooling with room temperature water is the universally recommended first step for mild burns to reduce pain, swelling, and prevent further tissue damage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCooling the burn with water at room temperature (typically 15-25°C or 59-77°F) helps dissipate heat from the injured tissue, thereby limiting the depth of the burn and reducing inflammation. This action minimizes pain by cooling nerve endings and prevents further cellular damage by halting the progression of the thermal injury. The recommended duration for cooling is generally 10-20 minutes, which is crucial for optimal therapeutic effect.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Placing ice directly on a burn can cause vasoconstriction, leading to further tissue damage, frostbite, and increased pain. It can also impair blood flow to the injured area, hindering the natural healing process.\nOption C (Incorrect): Applying butter or other greasy substances to a burn is an outdated and harmful practice. It can trap heat, increase the risk of infection by providing a medium for bacterial growth, and make wound cleaning more difficult for medical professionals.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Burn Degree | Appearance | First Aid |\n|---|---|---|\n| First-degree (superficial) | Red, non-blistered skin, painful | Cool water, pain relievers |\n| Second-degree (partial thickness) | Blisters, red, painful, swollen | Cool water, sterile dressing, medical evaluation |\n| Third-degree (full thickness) | White, leathery, charred, numb | Call emergency services, sterile dressing, medical evaluation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cool water for burns, never ice or grease.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nN/A\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Burn Association (ABA) guidelines (e.g., 2018 Practice Guidelines for Burn Care) recommend immediate cooling with cool water for thermal burns.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Wash by water with room\n \n  temperature | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Place an ice | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Put a butter | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
