  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Partial thickness burns: Painful, but not always a pain to heal!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A. Partial thickness burns, by definition, involve damage to the epidermis and a portion of the dermis, leaving nerve endings intact or irritated, which results in sensitivity and pain.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPartial thickness burns are characterized by the preservation of some dermal elements, including nerve endings. This allows for sensation, often manifesting as significant pain and sensitivity to touch, air currents, and temperature changes. The degree of sensitivity can vary; superficial partial thickness burns are typically very painful, while deep partial thickness burns may be less so due to more extensive nerve damage but are still generally sensitive, unlike full thickness burns where nerve endings are completely destroyed.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Insensitivity is characteristic of full thickness burns, where nerve endings are completely destroyed, not partial thickness burns.\nOption C (Incorrect): While deep partial thickness burns can have some non-viable tissue, the primary characteristic is not necessarily changing to slough within 2-3 weeks. Slough is more associated with full thickness burns or non-healing wounds, and many partial thickness burns heal by re-epithelialization.\nOption D (Incorrect): Not all partial thickness burns need a split graft. Superficial partial thickness burns heal spontaneously. Only deep partial thickness burns that are extensive or fail to heal may require grafting.\nOption E (Incorrect): Free flaps are complex reconstructive procedures used for large, deep tissue defects, often involving muscle or bone, and are not indicated for typical partial thickness burns.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Burn Depth | Appearance | Sensation | Healing Time | Treatment |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Superficial (1st degree) | Red, no blisters | Painful | 3-6 days | Symptomatic |\n| Superficial Partial Thickness (2nd degree) | Red, moist, blisters | Very painful, sensitive | 1-3 weeks | Wound care, sometimes grafting |\n| Deep Partial Thickness (2nd degree) | Red/white, dry, less blanching | Painful, pressure sensation | 3-9 weeks | Wound care, often grafting |\n| Full Thickness (3rd degree) | White, leathery, charred | Insensitive | Never (without intervention) | Excision, grafting |\n| Fourth Degree | Extends to bone/muscle | Insensitive | Never | Amputation, complex reconstruction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: If it hurts, it's likely partial thickness; if it doesn't, think full thickness.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a partial thickness burn will often blanch with pressure and refill, indicating some vascularity. Nerve endings may be visible or stimulated, causing patient discomfort if not adequately anesthetized. There are no specific imaging findings for burn depth.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Burn Association (ABA) Practice Guidelines for Burn Care (2018). Recommends early assessment of burn depth and appropriate wound care based on depth and extent.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Sensitive\n \n  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Insensitive. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Will change to slough within 2-3 weeks. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Needs a split graft. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Needs a free flap. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
