  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Full-thickness burns: No pain, all layers gone, graft needed.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Full thickness. A full-thickness burn, also known as a third-degree burn, involves the complete destruction of the epidermis, dermis, and often extends into the subcutaneous tissue, thus affecting all three primary layers of the skin.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe skin is anatomically composed of three main layers: the epidermis (outermost protective layer), the dermis (containing connective tissue, hair follicles, sweat glands, nerves, and blood vessels), and the subcutaneous tissue (hypodermis, primarily fat and loose connective tissue). A burn that penetrates and destroys all these layers results in a loss of skin integrity, sensation, and often requires surgical intervention like skin grafting for definitive closure due to the inability of the skin to regenerate from residual adnexal structures.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Partial thickness): Incorrect. Partial-thickness burns involve the epidermis and only a portion of the dermis, not all three layers.\nOption C (Superficial): Incorrect. Superficial burns (first-degree) are limited to the epidermis only.\nOption D (Deep): Incorrect. While 'deep' can describe a severe burn, 'full thickness' is the precise classification for burns involving all three layers of the skin.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Burn Depth | Layers Involved | Clinical Appearance | Sensation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Superficial (1st degree) | Epidermis | Red, blanches, dry | Painful |\n| Partial Thickness (2nd degree) | Epidermis, part of dermis | Red, blistered, moist, blanches | Very painful |\n| Full Thickness (3rd degree) | Epidermis, dermis, subcutaneous tissue | White, leathery, charred, non-blanching | Painless |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Full thickness burns destroy all skin layers, requiring grafting.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the operating room, a full-thickness burn would present as dry, leathery, waxy white, or charred tissue that is insensate to pinprick. There would be no capillary refill, indicating complete vascular destruction. Excision of this non-viable tissue and subsequent skin grafting would be the necessary surgical approach.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Burn Association (ABA) Practice Guidelines for Burn Care (e.g., 2018). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the assessment, classification, and management of burn injuries, emphasizing accurate depth determination.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Partial thickness | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Full\n \n  thickness | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Superficial | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Deep | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
