  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Painless burn? Think full-thickness, think specialist referral!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption C is the correct answer. A painless area with no blisters, explicitly described as a third-degree, full-thickness burn, always warrants referral to a burn clinician specialist due to the destruction of all skin layers and underlying structures.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFull-thickness (third-degree) burns involve complete destruction of the epidermis and dermis, extending into subcutaneous tissue. This destruction includes nerve endings, leading to the characteristic painless presentation. The absence of blisters is also typical as the skin is leathery or charred. These burns do not heal spontaneously and require surgical intervention, such as debridement and skin grafting, to prevent infection, minimize scarring, and restore function, necessitating specialist care.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): A 10 cm painful area with no blisters describes a first-degree (superficial) burn. These burns involve only the epidermis, are painful, red, and blanchable, but do not blister and typically heal spontaneously without specialist intervention.\nOption B (Incorrect): A 5 cm painful area with blisters describes a second-degree (partial-thickness) burn. While painful and characterized by blisters, a small, isolated partial-thickness burn often can be managed in an outpatient setting without specialist referral, unless it involves critical areas, is circumferential, or covers a large total body surface area.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Burn Depth | Appearance | Pain Level | Referral to Specialist |\n|:---|:---|:---|:---|\n| First Degree (Superficial) | Red, dry, blanches with pressure, no blisters | Painful | Rarely, unless extensive or critical location |\n| Second Degree (Partial Thickness) | Red, moist, blistered, blanches with pressure | Very painful | Yes, if large TBSA, critical location, or deep partial thickness |\n| Third Degree (Full Thickness) | Leathery, waxy, white, charred, no blanching, no blisters | Painless | Always |\n| Fourth Degree | Extends into muscle/bone | Painless | Always, often requires amputation/reconstruction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Any full-thickness burn, regardless of size, requires specialist burn referral.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging is not typically used for initial burn depth assessment. Intraoperatively, a full-thickness burn appears as non-viable, leathery, or charred tissue that does not bleed when incised, indicating complete dermal destruction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Burn Association (ABA) Burn Center Referral Criteria (2018) recommends referral for all full-thickness burns, regardless of size, and partial-thickness burns greater than 10% TBSA or involving critical areas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 10 cm painful area with no blusters | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 5 cm painful area with blusters | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 5 cm painless area with no blusters (third degree, full\n \n  thickness). | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
