  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Face and neck burns: Admit first, ask questions later!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, which states to apply something and admit the patient to the hospital. This is correct because any burn to the face or neck, regardless of perceived mildness, necessitates hospital admission due to the high risk of airway compromise and the need for specialized care.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBurns to the face and neck are critical due to their proximity to the airway. Even seemingly superficial burns can cause significant edema, leading to rapid airway obstruction. Furthermore, these areas require meticulous wound care to prevent infection, minimize scarring, and preserve function (e.g., eyes, mouth). The potential for inhalation injury, even without obvious signs, also mandates close observation in an inpatient setting. Early admission allows for proactive airway management, pain control, and specialized burn unit consultation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Discharging a patient with a facial or neck burn, or managing them solely with outpatient follow-up, is dangerous. It risks missing critical airway compromise, inadequate pain management, and potential complications like infection or severe scarring that could have been prevented with inpatient care.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Burn Characteristic | Admission Criteria | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Face/Neck Burns** | Always admit | High risk of airway compromise, inhalation injury, specialized wound care, cosmetic importance |\n| Hands/Feet/Perineum/Major Joints | Always admit | Functional impairment, specialized wound care, high risk of infection |\n| Partial Thickness Burns | >10% TBSA in adults, >5% in children | Fluid resuscitation, systemic effects, pain management |\n| Full Thickness Burns | Any size | Complex wound care, potential for grafting, systemic effects |\n| Circumferential Burns | Any location | Risk of compartment syndrome, neurovascular compromise |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Facial/neck burns = airway risk = admit, always.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn physical examination, one would look for signs of airway compromise such as stridor, hoarseness, soot in the nares/mouth, singed nasal hairs, or circumferential neck burns. During bronchoscopy, one might observe mucosal edema, erythema, or carbonaceous deposits in the tracheobronchial tree, indicating inhalation injury.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Burn Association (ABA) Practice Guidelines for Burn Care (2018) recommends admission for all facial and neck burns to a burn center or appropriate facility.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Apply (something) and admit the patient to the\n \n  hospital | ✅ Correct |\n| B | The rest of choices said apply (something) and discharge the patient /or fo | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) remember burn on the face necessitate admission** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
