  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bloody nipple? Papilloma's the usual suspect, but don't rule out cancer!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nIntraductal papilloma is the most common cause of pathological nipple discharge, a symptom that often prompts surgical evaluation. This benign lesion arises within the lactiferous ducts and is characterized by spontaneous, unilateral, and often bloody or serous discharge from a single duct.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntraductal papillomas are benign epithelial proliferations within the breast ducts, typically located in the major ducts near the nipple (central papillomas). Their friable nature and location within the duct lumen lead to bleeding or serous fluid accumulation, which then presents as nipple discharge. The characteristic presentation of spontaneous, unilateral, single-duct discharge is a critical indicator for surgical consultation and often necessitates microdochectomy for definitive diagnosis and treatment, as it can mimic or coexist with malignancy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (High prolactin level) (Incorrect): High prolactin levels cause galactorrhea, which is typically bilateral, multi-ductal, and milky or clear. While common, it represents a physiological or endocrine cause of nipple discharge, distinct from the pathological discharge that warrants surgical investigation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause | Type of Discharge | Laterality/Ducts | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Intraductal Papilloma | Serous, bloody, clear | Unilateral, single duct | Excision (microdochectomy) |\n| High Prolactin (Galactorrhea) | Milky, clear | Bilateral, multi-ductal | Medical (dopamine agonists), address underlying cause |\n| Duct Ectasia | Green, brown, sticky | Unilateral or bilateral, multi-ductal | Conservative, sometimes excision for persistent symptoms |\n| Breast Cancer | Bloody, serous | Unilateral, single duct | Biopsy, surgical oncology |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unilateral, single-duct discharge? Think papilloma or cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, mammography is often normal or shows non-specific findings. Ultrasound may reveal a dilated duct or an intraductal mass. Ductography (galactography) can visualize a filling defect within the duct. Intraoperatively, microdochectomy involves excising the affected duct, where the papilloma appears as a small, friable lesion within the lumen.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Breast Cancer Screening and Diagnosis (2023). These guidelines recommend a thorough evaluation of pathological nipple discharge, including clinical examination, imaging (mammography, ultrasound), and often surgical excision of the involved duct for definitive diagnosis and management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | High prolactin level | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Intraductal\n \n  papilloma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
