  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Slow bleed, slow dread: SDH is the progressive headache's friend.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. The most likely diagnosis is Subdural Hematoma (SDH). This is because a progressive headache over days following head trauma, even seemingly minor, is highly characteristic of a subdural hematoma, which typically involves slower venous bleeding.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSubdural hematomas result from the tearing of bridging veins that cross the subdural space, connecting the cerebral cortex to the dural venous sinuses. This venous bleeding is often slower than arterial bleeds, leading to a gradual accumulation of blood and a progressive onset of symptoms like headache, confusion, or focal neurological deficits over days to weeks. The relatively minor trauma from a ping pong ball can still cause sufficient shear forces to tear these delicate veins, especially in patients with cerebral atrophy (e.g., elderly, alcoholics) where the bridging veins are stretched.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (SAH - Subarachnoid Hemorrhage) (Incorrect): SAH typically presents with a sudden, severe 'thunderclap' headache, often described as the 'worst headache of my life,' rather than a progressive headache over days. While traumatic SAH can occur, the mechanism of injury (ping pong ball) is less likely to cause significant SAH compared to SDH, and the symptom progression does not fit the classic SAH presentation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Subdural Hematoma (SDH) | Subarachnoid Hemorrhage (SAH) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Bleeding Source** | Bridging veins | Arterial (e.g., aneurysm rupture) or small pial vessels |\n| **Onset of Symptoms** | Gradual, progressive (days to weeks) | Sudden, 'thunderclap' headache |\n| **Trauma Association** | Often associated with minor trauma, especially in elderly | Can be traumatic, but often spontaneous (aneurysm) |\n| **CT Appearance** | Crescent-shaped, crosses suture lines, does not cross falx/tentorium | Fills sulci and cisterns, star-shaped |\n| **Prognosis** | Variable, depends on size and mass effect | Often severe, high mortality/morbidity |\n| **Headache Quality** | Progressive, dull ache | Sudden, severe, 'worst headache of life' |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Progressive headache post-trauma = think SDH until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a non-contrast CT scan, an acute subdural hematoma appears as a crescent-shaped, hyperdense (bright white) collection of blood that conforms to the inner surface of the dura. It typically crosses suture lines but does not cross the falx cerebri or tentorium cerebelli. Chronic SDHs appear hypodense (dark) or isodense.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Brain Trauma Foundation Guidelines for the Management of Severe Traumatic Brain Injury (4th Edition, 2016) provide recommendations for the diagnosis and management of intracranial hematomas, including SDH.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | SAH. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | SDH.\n \n  | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
