  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't go IV unless the infection goes systemic!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient presents with localized signs of infection: left arm swelling and painful axillary lymphadenopathy. In the absence of systemic symptoms, oral antibiotics are the appropriate initial treatment for localized lymphadenitis or cellulitis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInitial management of localized skin and soft tissue infections, including lymphadenitis, often begins with empiric oral antibiotics targeting common skin flora (e.g., Staphylococcus aureus, Streptococcus pyogenes). The decision to use oral versus intravenous antibiotics hinges on the patient's overall clinical status, the extent of the infection, and the presence or absence of systemic inflammatory response syndrome (SIRS) criteria. For uncomplicated, localized infections without signs of sepsis or systemic compromise, oral therapy is effective, cost-efficient, and avoids the risks associated with IV access.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): IV antibiotics are indicated for more severe infections, those with systemic symptoms (fever, chills, malaise, hemodynamic instability), rapidly progressing infections, or failure of oral therapy. The question does not provide information suggesting systemic involvement.\nOption A (Correct): Oral antibiotics are the appropriate initial treatment for localized lymphadenitis or cellulitis when systemic symptoms are absent.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Oral Antibiotics |\n|---|---|\n| **Indication** | Localized infection, no systemic symptoms, stable patient |\n| **Examples** | Mild cellulitis, lymphadenitis, impetigo |\n| **Advantages** | Convenience, lower cost, fewer risks (e.g., line infection) |\n| **Disadvantages** | Compliance issues, variable absorption, slower onset |\n| **Feature** | IV Antibiotics |\n| **Indication** | Systemic symptoms, severe infection, immunocompromised, failed oral therapy |\n| **Examples** | Sepsis, necrotizing fasciitis, severe erysipelas, deep space infections |\n| **Advantages** | Rapid onset, higher tissue penetration, reliable absorption |\n| **Disadvantages** | Higher cost, need for IV access, increased risk of complications |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Localized infection without systemic symptoms = oral antibiotics first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound may show enlarged, hypoechoic lymph nodes with increased vascularity, and potentially subcutaneous edema consistent with cellulitis. CT scan could delineate deeper collections or abscesses if suspected.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInfectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Skin and Soft Tissue Infections (2014) recommend oral antibiotics for uncomplicated cellulitis without systemic signs.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | oral antibiotics (if only\n \n  lymphadenitis) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | IV antibiotics (if systematic symptoms) | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
