  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For stones, non-contrast CT is the undisputed champion!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nNon-contrast CT of the abdomen and pelvis is the most specific and sensitive imaging modality for diagnosing urolithiasis. It is considered the gold standard for evaluating patients with suspected kidney stones.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNon-contrast CT (NCCT) excels due to its ability to detect all types of urinary calculi, including radiolucent stones (e.g., uric acid stones) that are not visible on plain radiographs. It provides excellent anatomical detail, allowing for precise localization of the stone and identification of secondary signs of obstruction, such as hydronephrosis, perinephric fat stranding, and ureteral dilation. This comprehensive assessment contributes to its high sensitivity and specificity, making it superior for confirming the diagnosis and guiding management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): US (Ultrasound) is less sensitive than CT for detecting ureteral stones, especially in the mid-ureter, and cannot reliably identify stone composition. While useful for detecting hydronephrosis and larger stones in the kidney or vesicoureteral junction, its overall diagnostic accuracy for urolithiasis is inferior to NCCT.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Imaging Modality | Sensitivity for Urolithiasis | Specificity for Urolithiasis | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n| :--------------- | :--------------------------- | :--------------------------- | :--------- | :------------ |\n| Non-contrast CT  | 95-100%                      | 94-98%                       | Detects all stone types, identifies secondary signs, good for alternative diagnoses | Radiation exposure, cost |\n| Ultrasound       | 45-85%                       | 80-90%                       | No radiation, lower cost, good for hydronephrosis | Operator dependent, poor for ureteral stones, cannot characterize stone type |\n| KUB X-ray        | 50-60%                       | 70-80%                       | Low cost, low radiation | Misses radiolucent stones, poor sensitivity |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: NCCT is the gold standard for acute renal colic due to its high sensitivity and specificity.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn non-contrast CT, urinary stones appear as hyperdense (bright white) foci within the collecting system or ureter. Associated findings often include hydronephrosis (dilated renal pelvis and calyces), perinephric fat stranding, and ureteral wall edema (the 'rim sign').\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines for the Management of Ureteral Stones (2023) recommends non-contrast CT as the initial imaging modality for suspected urolithiasis in most patients presenting with acute flank pain.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | US | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | non contrast CT of abd &\n \n  pelvis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
