  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Antibiotics can cure one infection, but cause another.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption C, Pseudomembranous colitis, is the correct diagnosis. The key clinical clue is the history of recent antibiotic use (AB treatment 3 weeks prior), which is the primary risk factor for Clostridioides difficile infection (CDI), the cause of pseudomembranous colitis. The symptoms of diffuse abdominal pain, bleeding per rectum, and fever are consistent with severe CDI.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPseudomembranous colitis is caused by an overgrowth of Clostridioides difficile in the colon, typically following disruption of the normal gut flora by antibiotics. C. difficile produces toxins (Toxin A and Toxin B) that cause inflammation, mucosal damage, and the formation of characteristic pseudomembranes on the colonic mucosa. The symptoms of abdominal pain, fever, and bloody diarrhea (bleeding per rectum) reflect this severe colonic inflammation. The 3-week interval between antibiotic use and symptom onset is typical for CDI.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Ischemic colitis) (Incorrect): While ischemic colitis can present with abdominal pain and rectal bleeding, there is no specific risk factor mentioned in the history (e.g., atherosclerosis, hypoperfusion, vasculitis) that would strongly suggest ischemia over an infectious cause, especially given the recent antibiotic use.\nOption B (Amoebic colitis) (Incorrect): Amoebic colitis, caused by Entamoeba histolytica, presents with bloody diarrhea, abdominal pain, and fever. However, there is no epidemiological link (e.g., travel to endemic areas) or specific symptom pattern that would make it more likely than C. difficile infection in the context of recent antibiotic exposure.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Pseudomembranous Colitis | Ischemic Colitis | Amoebic Colitis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Etiology** | Clostridioides difficile toxins | Hypoperfusion/ischemia to colon | Entamoeba histolytica |\n| **Key Risk Factors** | Recent antibiotic use, hospitalization, advanced age | Atherosclerosis, hypovolemia, cardiac disease, vasculitis | Travel to endemic areas, contaminated food/water |\n| **Typical Symptoms** | Diarrhea (often watery, can be bloody), abdominal pain, fever | Sudden onset abdominal pain (often left-sided), rectal bleeding, urgency | Bloody diarrhea, abdominal pain, fever, tenesmus |\n| **Diagnostic Test** | C. difficile toxin assay (stool), colonoscopy | CT angiography, colonoscopy | Stool microscopy for trophozoites/cysts, serology |\n| **Treatment** | Oral vancomycin or fidaxomicin | Supportive care, address underlying cause, surgery if severe | Metronidazole, then luminal agent |\n\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Recent antibiotic use + GI symptoms = C. diff until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, findings may include colonic wall thickening, pericolic fat stranding, and ascites. In severe cases, a 'target sign' or 'accordion sign' may be seen due to mucosal edema and pseudomembranes. Endoscopically, characteristic yellow-white plaques (pseudomembranes) are seen scattered over the inflamed colonic mucosa.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInfectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) 2021 Clinical Practice Guidelines for Clostridioides difficile Infection in Adults and Children. These guidelines recommend specific diagnostic tests and treatment regimens based on disease severity.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ischemic colitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Amoebic colitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pseudomembranous\n \n  colitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
