  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Symptomatic AAA: CT confirms, US screens, MRI waits.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient's presentation with abdominal pain, back pain, and a pulsatile abdomen is highly suggestive of a symptomatic abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA), potentially expanding or ruptured. An abdominal CT scan is the most appropriate and definitive diagnostic step to confirm the diagnosis and assess for complications.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAbdominal CT provides rapid, high-resolution cross-sectional imaging that precisely delineates the aneurysm's size, extent, and relationship to renal arteries. Crucially, it can identify signs of rupture, such as retroperitoneal hemorrhage or active extravasation, which are critical for immediate management decisions and surgical planning.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Abdominal US) (Incorrect): While useful for initial screening and detecting an AAA, ultrasound is operator-dependent and less accurate for detailed anatomical assessment, especially in symptomatic patients or when rupture is suspected. It cannot reliably rule out rupture.\nOption C (Abdominal MRI) (Incorrect): MRI can diagnose AAA but is generally not the first-line imaging modality due to longer acquisition times, higher cost, and contraindications (e.g., pacemakers). CT is faster and more readily available for emergent situations.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Advantages | Disadvantages | Role in AAA |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Abdominal US | Non-invasive, no radiation, inexpensive, quick | Operator-dependent, limited by bowel gas/obesity, poor for rupture detection | Screening, initial diagnosis, surveillance |\n| Abdominal CT | Fast, high resolution, excellent for rupture detection, surgical planning | Radiation exposure, contrast nephrotoxicity risk | Definitive diagnosis, pre-operative planning, rupture assessment |\n| Abdominal MRI | No radiation, excellent soft tissue contrast | Longer scan time, higher cost, contraindications, less available | Alternative for contrast allergy or renal insufficiency, detailed wall assessment |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pulsatile mass + pain = AAA until proven otherwise; confirm with CT.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn abdominal CT, an AAA would appear as a focal dilation of the abdominal aorta, typically >3 cm in diameter. Signs of rupture might include retroperitoneal hematoma, loss of the aortic fat plane, or extravasation of contrast.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety for Vascular Surgery (SVS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Abdominal Aortic Aneurysms (2018). Recommends CT angiography for detailed anatomical assessment and surgical planning in patients with AAA.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Abdominal US | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Abdominal CT | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Abdominal MRI | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
