  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, cut it out... for a biopsy!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Biopsy. A huge leg ulcer with red, raised edges is highly suspicious for malignancy, such as squamous cell carcinoma (SCC) or a Marjolin's ulcer, and requires definitive tissue diagnosis before any treatment is initiated.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMalignant transformation, particularly squamous cell carcinoma, can occur in chronic wounds or present de novo as an ulcer with suspicious features. The description of 'raised edges' is a classic indicator of proliferative growth, often seen in SCC. A biopsy is the gold standard for diagnosing malignancy, providing histological confirmation of cell type and differentiation, which is crucial for guiding subsequent definitive treatment like surgical excision, radiation, or chemotherapy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Topical steroids) (Incorrect): Steroids can mask underlying malignancy, delay diagnosis, and are not appropriate for a suspicious ulcer. They might reduce inflammation but won't address the potential cancer.\nOption C (Radiotherapy) (Incorrect): Radiotherapy is a treatment modality for confirmed cancer, not a diagnostic step. It would only be considered after a biopsy has established a definitive diagnosis and staging.\nOption D (Topical antibiotics) (Incorrect): While ulcers can become infected, the primary concern with 'raised edges' is malignancy, not solely infection. Treating with antibiotics alone would delay the critical diagnostic biopsy and potentially allow a malignancy to progress.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Ulcer Type | Key Features | Initial Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| Venous Ulcer | Irregular, shallow, often around malleoli, associated with edema, hyperpigmentation | Compression, wound care, elevation |\n| Arterial Ulcer | Punched-out, painful, pale base, often on toes/pressure points, diminished pulses | Revascularization, wound care, pain control |\n| Neuropathic Ulcer | Painless, often on plantar foot/pressure areas, calloused edges, associated with neuropathy | Offloading, debridement, glycemic control |\n| Malignant Ulcer | Raised/everted edges, indurated, non-healing, often friable, can be huge | Biopsy (incisional or excisional) |\n| Marjolin's Ulcer | SCC arising in chronic scar/wound (e.g., burn, osteomyelitis sinus) | Biopsy, wide surgical excision |\n\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Suspicious ulcer with raised edges? Biopsy first, always.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThe question describes a 'Picture of a huge ulcer in the leg, the ulcer is red with raised edges.' This visual description is highly suggestive of malignancy. On examination, such an ulcer would appear indurated, potentially fixed to underlying structures, and may have areas of necrosis or fungating growth. A deep incisional or punch biopsy from the most suspicious, raised, and indurated edge is critical to obtain adequate tissue for histopathological diagnosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Squamous Cell Skin Cancer (2024) recommend biopsy as the definitive diagnostic step for suspicious skin lesions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Topical steroids | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Biopsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Radiotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Topical antibiotics | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
