  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Post-hemorrhoidectomy, the bladder often holds more than the bowels.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. The most common complication following hemorrhoidectomy is urinary retention. This is primarily due to perianal pain causing reflex bladder sphincter spasm, often exacerbated by opioid analgesia and local edema.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe intense pain associated with hemorrhoidectomy, particularly in the highly innervated perianal region, triggers a reflex spasm of the external urethral sphincter. This spasm, combined with the systemic effects of opioid pain medications (which decrease bladder detrusor contractility) and local tissue edema, significantly impairs the patient's ability to void. Early recognition and management are crucial to prevent bladder overdistension and potential long-term bladder dysfunction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Fecal impaction is a less immediate complication, often occurring later due to fear of painful defecation or opioid-induced constipation, not typically the most common immediate post-operative issue.\nOption B (Incorrect): While bleeding is a potential and serious complication, especially within the first 24 hours or around 7-10 days post-op, it is statistically less common than urinary retention in the immediate postoperative period.\nOption D (Incorrect): Infection is a relatively uncommon complication following hemorrhoidectomy, thanks to good surgical technique, bowel preparation, and sometimes prophylactic antibiotics, making it less frequent than urinary retention.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Timing | Cause | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Urinary Retention | Immediate post-op | Pain, spasm, opioids | Catheterization, alpha-blockers |\n| Bleeding | Immediate or 7-10 days | Inadequate hemostasis, sloughing | Re-operation, cautery |\n| Fecal Impaction | Early post-op | Pain, opioids, fear of defecation | Stool softeners, enemas |\n| Anal Stenosis | Late | Excessive tissue removal, scarring | Dilatation, anoplasty |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Perianal pain post-hemorrhoidectomy often leads to urinary retention.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the surgeon must ensure meticulous hemostasis to prevent bleeding. Postoperatively, a distended bladder can be palpated suprapubically or confirmed with a bladder scan showing significant residual volume.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Hemorrhoids (2018). These guidelines emphasize adequate pain control and monitoring for urinary retention post-hemorrhoidectomy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | fecal impaction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | bleeding | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | urinary retention | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | infection | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
