  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Nighttime rectal pain, a fleeting spasm's reign.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct diagnosis for an old man presenting with rectal pain mostly at night, accompanied by itching, is Proctalgia fugax. This condition is characterized by sudden, severe, episodic rectal pain, often occurring at night and waking the patient from sleep, making it the most fitting option given the nocturnal pain pattern.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nProctalgia fugax is a functional anorectal disorder characterized by transient, severe, spasmodic rectal pain. The pain is typically short-lived, lasting seconds to minutes, and resolves spontaneously. Its hallmark is the nocturnal occurrence, often waking patients from sleep, which strongly aligns with the patient's complaint of pain 'mostly at night'. The underlying mechanism is thought to be a spasm of the internal anal sphincter or the levator ani muscle. While itching is not a primary symptom of proctalgia fugax, it can be a co-existing condition (pruritus ani) or a secondary discomfort from severe pain.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Hemorrhoids typically cause pain associated with defecation, prolonged sitting, or thrombosis, not predominantly nocturnal pain. While itching (pruritus ani) can be worse at night, the primary pain pattern doesn't fit.\nOption B (Incorrect): \"Gay bowel syndrome\" is an outdated and non-specific term for various anorectal conditions, often infectious or inflammatory. It does not describe a specific diagnosis with a characteristic nocturnal pain pattern.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Pain Characteristics | Associated Symptoms | Etiology/Pathophysiology |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Proctalgia Fugax | Sudden, severe, episodic, spasmodic rectal pain; often nocturnal, waking patient from sleep; short-lived (seconds to minutes). | None specific; can be associated with stress. | Spasm of the internal anal sphincter or levator ani muscle. |\n| Levator Ani Syndrome | Chronic, dull, aching, pressure-like pain in the rectum/perineum; worse with sitting, relieved by lying down. | Tenderness on palpation of levator ani muscles. | Chronic tension or spasm of the levator ani muscle. |\n| Hemorrhoids | Pain with defecation, prolonged sitting, or thrombosis; often described as throbbing or aching. | Bleeding (bright red), itching (pruritus ani), prolapse, mucus discharge. | Engorgement and displacement of anal cushions. |\n| Pruritus Ani | Intense perianal itching, often worse at night or after bowel movements. | Skin excoriation, erythema, lichenification. | Various causes: poor hygiene, dermatological conditions, infections, hemorrhoids, diet. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Nocturnal rectal pain, especially episodic, points to proctalgia fugax.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThere are no specific imaging findings for Proctalgia fugax; it is a diagnosis of exclusion based on clinical symptoms after ruling out other organic causes. Endoscopy or imaging may be used to exclude other pathologies.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Functional Anorectal Disorders (2021) recommends a thorough history and physical exam to diagnose proctalgia fugax and rule out other causes of anorectal pain.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hemorrhoids | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Gay bowel syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Proctalgia fugax | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
