  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Sudden, severe, nocturnal rectal pain? Think fugax!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Proctalgia fugax. This diagnosis perfectly aligns with the patient's presentation of painful rectal spasms, diaphoresis, and tachycardia, especially at night, which are classic symptoms of this benign condition.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nProctalgia fugax is characterized by sudden, severe, and short-lived episodes of rectal pain, often occurring at night and waking the patient from sleep. The pain is thought to be due to a spasm of the smooth muscle of the rectum or anal canal. The autonomic symptoms like diaphoresis and tachycardia are a physiological response to the intense, albeit brief, pain. It is a functional disorder, meaning there is no identifiable structural abnormality.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Thrombosed hemorrhoid: This condition typically presents with constant, severe perianal pain associated with a palpable, tender lump, not intermittent rectal spasms, and is less likely to be exclusively nocturnal.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Proctalgia Fugax | Levator Ani Syndrome | Thrombosed Hemorrhoid |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Pain Character** | Sudden, severe, brief, spasmodic | Dull ache, pressure, constant, worse with sitting | Constant, severe, sharp, throbbing |\n| **Timing** | Nocturnal, wakes from sleep | Worse with prolonged sitting, relieved by lying down | Acute onset, persistent |\n| **Associated Symptoms** | Diaphoresis, tachycardia, anxiety | Feeling of rectal fullness, tenesmus | Palpable, tender perianal lump, bleeding |\n| **Etiology** | Rectal/anal muscle spasm (functional) | Spasm/inflammation of levator ani muscle | Acute thrombosis of external hemorrhoidal plexus |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Nocturnal, severe, brief rectal spasms = Proctalgia fugax.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNo specific imaging findings are typically seen for Proctalgia fugax as it is a functional disorder. Endoscopy would also be normal.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nRome IV Criteria for Functional Anorectal Pain (2016). These criteria define Proctalgia fugax as recurrent episodes of anal pain, lasting seconds to minutes, with no identifiable cause.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Thrombosed hemorrhoid | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Proctalgia fugax | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
