  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Shave smart, treat infection, avoid steroids.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is oral antibiotics. For bacterial folliculitis that is widespread, severe, or unresponsive to topical treatments, systemic antibiotics are the appropriate course of action to eradicate the infection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBacterial folliculitis, often caused by *Staphylococcus aureus*, presents as inflamed, pus-filled lesions around hair follicles. Oral antibiotics, such as cephalexin or doxycycline, achieve therapeutic concentrations in the skin and hair follicles, effectively targeting the causative bacteria and resolving the infection. This systemic approach is crucial when the infection is extensive or deep-seated, or when topical treatments have failed.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Oral steroids suppress the immune system and can exacerbate bacterial infections, making them generally contraindicated for primary treatment of bacterial folliculitis. They are reserved for severe inflammatory conditions without active infection.\nOption B (Incorrect): Topical steroids reduce inflammation but do not treat the underlying bacterial cause of folliculitis. While useful for inflammatory conditions like pseudofolliculitis barbae, they are not appropriate for bacterial folliculitis and can potentially worsen it by masking symptoms or promoting bacterial growth.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | First-line Treatment | Second-line/Severe Treatment |\n|---|---|---|\n| Bacterial Folliculitis (mild) | Topical antibiotics (e.g., mupirocin, clindamycin) | Oral antibiotics (e.g., cephalexin, doxycycline) |\n| Pseudofolliculitis Barbae | Shaving modification, topical retinoids | Topical steroids, laser hair removal |\n| Fungal Folliculitis (Tinea Barbae) | Topical antifungals | Oral antifungals (e.g., terbinafine, itraconazole) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Treat bacterial folliculitis with antibiotics, not steroids.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFolliculitis typically presents as erythematous papules or pustules centered around hair follicles. No specific imaging is usually required for diagnosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Dermatology (AAD) guidelines for skin infections recommend topical antibiotics for localized bacterial folliculitis and oral antibiotics for more extensive, deep, or refractory cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | oral steroid | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | topical steroid | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | oral antibiotics | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) maybe there was topical antifungal but no topical antibiotic choice** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
