  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When a neck mass whispers, CT neck listens loudest.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is CT neck. A palpable mid-cervical mass, even with mild hoarseness, necessitates detailed anatomical characterization to determine its nature and extent. CT neck provides comprehensive imaging of the mass and surrounding structures, including the larynx and potential nerve involvement.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCT neck is the gold standard for evaluating cervical masses. it offers excellent spatial resolution, allowing for precise localization, assessment of size, internal characteristics (solid, cystic, necrotic), and relationship to critical neurovascular structures and the aerodigestive tract. This information is crucial for surgical planning or further diagnostic steps like biopsy, and helps to elucidate the cause of hoarseness if it's related to the mass.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Indirect laryngoscopy is essential for evaluating hoarseness by visualizing the vocal cords, but it does not characterize the palpable mid-cervical mass itself. It's a complementary, not the primary, investigation for a mass.\nOption B (Incorrect): CT brain is irrelevant for a mid-cervical mass. While hoarseness can rarely have central causes, a palpable neck mass points to a local etiology.\nOption D (Incorrect): A throat swab is used to diagnose infectious causes of pharyngitis or tonsillitis, not to investigate a palpable cervical mass or chronic hoarseness.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Investigation | Primary Use | Information Provided |\n|---|---|---|\n| CT Neck | Characterize neck masses | Size, location, internal features, relation to vital structures, extent of disease |\n| Indirect Laryngoscopy | Evaluate hoarseness | Vocal cord mobility, lesions on vocal cords/larynx |\n| Ultrasound Neck | Initial evaluation of neck masses | Solid vs. cystic, vascularity, guide biopsy |\n| MRI Neck | Soft tissue detail, perineural spread | Better for soft tissue differentiation, nerve involvement, skull base extension |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: A palpable neck mass + symptom = CT neck for characterization.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT neck, a mid-cervical mass would be visualized, allowing assessment of its density, enhancement pattern, and relationship to the thyroid gland, strap muscles, carotid sheath, and larynx. For example, a thyroid nodule might show calcifications, while a branchial cleft cyst would appear as a well-defined cystic lesion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Hoarseness (Dysphonia) (2018) recommends imaging (CT or MRI) for hoarseness associated with a neck mass or other concerning features.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Indirect laryngoscope | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | CT brain | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | CT neck | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Throat swab | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi.pdf**\n",
